{"title_page": "My Funny Valentine", "text_new": "{{for|the albums|My Funny Valentine (Miles Davis album)|My Funny Valentine (Frederica von Stade album)|My Funny Valentine (Larry Willis album)}}\n{{short description|Song by Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart from the 1937 musical \"Babes in Arms\"}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Funny Valentine\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1937 by [[Chappell & Co.]]\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Lorenz Hart]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''My Funny Valentine'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1937 [[Richard Rodgers]] and [[Lorenz Hart]] musical ''[[Babes in Arms]]'' in which it was introduced by former child star [[Mitzi Green]]. The song became a popular [[jazz standard]], appearing on over 1300 albums performed by over 600 artists. In 2015, it was announced that the [[Gerry Mulligan]] quartet featuring [[Chet Baker]]'s version of the song was inducted into the [[National Recording Registry|Library of Congress's National Recording Registry]] for the song's \"cultural, artistic and/or historical significance to American society and the nation\u2019s audio legacy\". Mulligan also recorded the song with his Concert Jazz Band in 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2015/15-041.html | title=National Recording Registry To \"Ac-Cent-Tchu-Ate the Positive\" | work=The Library of Congress | date=25 March 2015 | accessdate=25 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623180708/http://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2015/15-041.html |archivedate=23 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe song is usually performed in C minor, although for vocalists the key of B minor is fairly common. [[Frank Sinatra]] recorded the song in B minor, and the theatrical version was also in B minor. [[Ella Fitzgerald]] recorded the song in G minor.\n\nThe song follows the following chord progression (in the key of C minor):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7/C\n|Fm7\n|D\u23007\n|G7(b9)\n|}\nThe second A section follows a similar progression, but the last two bars are replaced with a minor ii-V in Eb heading into the bridge.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7/C\n|Fm7\n|F\u23007\n|Bb7(b9)\n|}\nThe bridge is in the relative major and speeds up the harmonic progression to 2 chords per measure:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Ebmaj7  Fm7\n|Gm7  Fm7\n|Ebmaj7  Fm7\n|Gm7  Fm7\n|-\n|Ebmaj7  G7\n|Cm7  Bbm7 A7\n|Abmaj7\n|D\u23007   G7\n|}\nThe last A section is extended by 4 bars:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7\n|D\u23007  G7(b9)\n|Cm7\n|Bbm7 A7\n|-\n|Abmaj7\n|Fm7  Bb7(b9)\n|Eb6\n|D\u23007   G7\n|}\n*\n\nThis simple and classic structure makes it easy to adapt to other genres and for jazz musicians to improvise over the established chords.\n\n==History==\n''[[Babes in Arms]]'' opened at the [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], in [[New York City]] on April 14, 1937 and ran for 289 performances.<ref>{{cite book |last=Trager |first=James |year=2005 |title=The People's Chronology: A Year-by-Year Record of Human Events from Prehistory to the Present |edition=3 |location=Detroit |publisher=Gale |isbn=0805031340}}</ref> In the original play, a character named Billie Smith (played by [[Mitzi Green]]) sings the song to Valentine \"Val\" LaMar (played by [[Ray Heatherton]]).<ref>Playbill from 1937 ''Babes in Arms'' theatrical performance.</ref> In the song, Billie pokes fun at some of Valentine's characteristics, but ultimately affirms that he makes her smile and that she doesn't want him to change (the song is often sung by a man to a woman, though to say that a woman's looks are \"laughable\" is anomalous).\n\nThe song first hit the charts in 1945, performed by [[Hal McIntyre]] with vocals by Ruth Gaylor.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Orodenker |first= M. H. |date=1945-01-27 |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=whEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title= Popular Record Reviews |volume=27 |issue=4 |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> It only appeared for one week and hit #16.<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |year=1992 |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954: The History of American Popular Music |publisher=Record Research, Inc |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit }} As cited in [http://www.jazzstandards.com/compositions-0/myfunnyvalentine.htm My Funny Valentine (1937)], written, compiled, and published by jazzstandards.com.</ref>\n\n[[Bing Crosby]] recorded the song in 1956<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/CBS.html |website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> for use on his [[The Bing Crosby Show (1954\u20131956)|radio show]] and it was subsequently included in the box set ''The Bing Crosby CBS Radio Recordings (1954-56)'' issued by [[Mosaic Records]] (catalog MD7-245) in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=allmusic.com|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-bing-crosby-cbs-radio-recordings-1954-56-mw0001951404|website=allmusic.com|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Elvis Costello]] recorded a cover version in 1978. It came out in 1979 as the B-side of the single [[Oliver's Army]] and was later included in multiple compilation albums.\n\n[[Michael Buble]] recorded the song for his 2018 album [[Love (Michael Bubl\u00e9 album)|Love]].\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In [[The Simpsons]] Season 29 episode ''[[Haw-Haw Land]]'', [[Nelson Muntz]] sings \"My Funny Valentine\" to [[Lisa Simpson]]. The Frank Sinatra version is later used in the same episode.\n* The song was featured in 1999 film [[The Talented Mr. Ripley (film)|The Talented Mr. Ripley]].\n* In Part 7 of [[Hirohiko Araki]]'s long-running Japanese manga series [[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure]], entitled [[Steel Ball Run]], the main antagonist, the president of the United States, is named Funny Valentine. The series is known for its many references to pop culture, particularly with regards to music, making this a reference to the song.\n* In ''[[The Good Cop (American TV series)|The Good Cop]]'' Season 1 episode ''Did the TV Star Do It?'', Tony Caruso Sr., played by [[Tony Danza]] starts to sing \"My Funny Valentine\" on TV, but the murderer/TV host pretends to be offended by what he claims are the misogynistic lyrics.  He then fires Tony Sr, allowing him to claim Tony Jr. is out for revenge when he arrests the murderer.\n*In the 1998 anime series directed by Shinichiro Watanabe [[Cowboy Bebop]] the main character Faye Valentine's name is directly attributed to the song.\n*In the 1995 Season 2 Episode of \"Living Single, entitled \"Singing the Blues\" Kyle Barker (T.C Carson) Sings \"My Funny Valentine\" to his on again/ off again rival and lover Max [Maxine Shaw (Erika Alexander) in an attempt to regain his confidence after an earlier performance was derailed by her presence. She is left swooning by the end of the number. In 2015 he covered the song on a single.\n* The song was used in ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' episode Engagement.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web |last=Bragalini |first=Luca |year=1997 |title=My Funny Valentine: The Disintegration of the Standard |url=http://www.plosin.com/milesAhead/Valentine.html |publisher=Originally published in Musica Jazz}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Cook |first=Richard |date=1999-02-12 |title=The Hart of the Matter |journal=New Statesman |volume=128 |issue=4423 |page=45 |issn=1364-7431}}\n* {{cite book |last=Fox |first=Dan |year=2007 |title=World's Greatest Wedding Music: 50 of the Most Requested Wedding Pieces |publisher=Alfred Music Publishing |isbn=0-7390-4674-8 |page=}}\n* {{cite book |last=Friedwald |first=Will |authorlink=Will Friedwald |year=2002 |chapter=My Funny Valentine (1937) |title=Stardust Memories: The Biography of Twelve of America's Most Popular Songs |location=New York |publisher=Random House, Inc |isbn=0-375-42089-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/stardustmelodies00frie/page/348 348\u2013373] |url=https://archive.org/details/stardustmelodies00frie/page/348 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Gabbard |first=Krin |year=2004 |title=Black Magic: White Hollywood and African American Culture |url=https://archive.org/details/blackmagicwhiteh0000gabb |url-access=registration |publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=0-8135-3384-8 |page=}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hischak |first=Thomas S.|year=2007 |title=The Rodgers and Hammerstein Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Press |isbn=0-313-34140-0|page=189}}\n* {{cite book |last=Holbrook |first=Morris B. |editors=Steve Lannin and Matthew Caley |year=2005 |chapter=The Ambi-Diegesis of \"My Funny Valentine\" |title=Pop fiction: The Song in Cinema |isbn=1-84150-078-X |location=Portland, OR |publisher=Intellect Books |pages=48\u201362}}\n* {{cite book |last=Studwell |first=William Emmett |year=1994 |title=The Popular Song Reader: A Sampler of Well-Known Twentieth Century-Songs |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1-56024-369-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/popularsongreade0000stud/page/127 127] |url=https://archive.org/details/popularsongreade0000stud/page/127 }}\n\n{{Rodgers and Hart}}\n\n[[Category:1937 songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Lorenz Hart]]\n[[Category:Ella Fitzgerald songs]]\n[[Category:Frank Sinatra songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:Ronnie Milsap songs]]\n[[Category:Eartha Kitt songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from Babes in Arms]]\n[[Category:Songs from Pal Joey (film)]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B minor]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in C minor]]\n[[Category:American songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Chaka Khan songs]]\n[[Category:Anita Baker songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the albums|My Funny Valentine (Miles Davis album)|My Funny Valentine (Frederica von Stade album)|My Funny Valentine (Larry Willis album)}}\n{{short description|Song by Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart from the 1937 musical \"Babes in Arms\"}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = My Funny Valentine\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1937 by [[Chappell & Co.]]\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Lorenz Hart]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''My Funny Valentine'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the 1937 [[Richard Rodgers]] and [[Lorenz Hart]] musical ''[[Babes in Arms]]'' in which it was introduced by former child star [[Mitzi Green]]. The song became a popular [[jazz standard]], appearing on over 1300 albums performed by over 600 artists. In 2015, it was announced that the [[Gerry Mulligan]] quartet featuring [[Chet Baker]]'s version of the song was inducted into the [[National Recording Registry|Library of Congress's National Recording Registry]] for the song's \"cultural, artistic and/or historical significance to American society and the nation\u2019s audio legacy\". Mulligan also recorded the song with his Concert Jazz Band in 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2015/15-041.html | title=National Recording Registry To \"Ac-Cent-Tchu-Ate the Positive\" | work=The Library of Congress | date=25 March 2015 | accessdate=25 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623180708/http://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2015/15-041.html |archivedate=23 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe song is usually performed in C minor, although for vocalists the key of B minor is fairly common. [[Frank Sinatra]] recorded the song in B minor, and the theatrical version was also in B minor. [[Ella Fitzgerald]] recorded the song in G minor.\n\nThe song follows the following chord progression (in the key of C minor):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7/C\n|Fm7\n|D\u23007\n|G7(b9)\n|}\nThe second A section follows a similar progression, but the last two bars are replaced with a minor ii-V in Eb heading into the bridge.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7/C\n|Fm7\n|F\u23007\n|Bb7(b9)\n|}\nThe bridge is in the relative major and speeds up the harmonic progression to 2 chords per measure:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Ebmaj7  Fm7\n|Gm7  Fm7\n|Ebmaj7  Fm7\n|Gm7  Fm7\n|-\n|Ebmaj7  G7\n|Cm7  Bbm7 A7\n|Abmaj7\n|D\u23007   G7\n|}\nThe last A section is extended by 4 bars:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Cm\n|Cm(M7)\n|Cm7\n|Cm6\n|-\n|Abmaj7\n|D\u23007  G7(b9)\n|Cm7\n|Bbm7 A7\n|-\n|Abmaj7\n|Fm7  Bb7(b9)\n|Eb6\n|D\u23007   G7\n|}\n*\n\nThis simple and classic structure makes it easy to adapt to other genres and for jazz musicians to improvise over the established chords.\n\n==History==\n''[[Babes in Arms]]'' opened at the [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], in [[New York City]] on April 14, 1937 and ran for 289 performances.<ref>{{cite book |last=Trager |first=James |year=2005 |title=The People's Chronology: A Year-by-Year Record of Human Events from Prehistory to the Present |edition=3 |location=Detroit |publisher=Gale |isbn=0805031340}}</ref> In the original play, a character named Billie Smith (played by [[Mitzi Green]]) sings the song to Valentine \"Val\" LaMar (played by [[Ray Heatherton]]).<ref>Playbill from 1937 ''Babes in Arms'' theatrical performance.</ref> In the song, Billie pokes fun at some of Valentine's characteristics, but ultimately affirms that he makes her smile and that she doesn't want him to change (the song is often sung by a man to a woman, though to say that a woman's looks are \"laughable\" is anomalous).\n\nThe song first hit the charts in 1945, performed by [[Hal McIntyre]] with vocals by Ruth Gaylor.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Orodenker |first= M. H. |date=1945-01-27 |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=whEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title= Popular Record Reviews |volume=27 |issue=4 |issn=0006-2510}}</ref> It only appeared for one week and hit #16.<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |year=1992 |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954: The History of American Popular Music |publisher=Record Research, Inc |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit }} As cited in [http://www.jazzstandards.com/compositions-0/myfunnyvalentine.htm My Funny Valentine (1937)], written, compiled, and published by jazzstandards.com.</ref>\n\n[[Bing Crosby]] recorded the song in 1956<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/CBS.html |website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> for use on his [[The Bing Crosby Show (1954\u20131956)|radio show]] and it was subsequently included in the box set ''The Bing Crosby CBS Radio Recordings (1954-56)'' issued by [[Mosaic Records]] (catalog MD7-245) in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=allmusic.com|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-bing-crosby-cbs-radio-recordings-1954-56-mw0001951404|website=allmusic.com|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Elvis Costello]] recorded a cover version in 1978. It came out in 1979 as the B-side of the single [[Oliver's Army]] and was later included in multiple compilation albums.\n\n[[Michael Buble]] recorded the song for his 2018 album [[Love (Michael Bubl\u00e9 album)|Love]].\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In [[The Simpsons]] Season 29 episode ''[[Haw Haw Land]]'', [[Nelson Muntz]] sings \"My Funny Valentine\" to [[Lisa Simpson]]. The Frank Sinatra version is later used in the same episode.\n* The song was featured in 1999 film [[The Talented Mr. Ripley (film)|The Talented Mr. Ripley]].\n* In Part 7 of [[Hirohiko Araki]]'s long-running Japanese manga series [[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure]], entitled [[Steel Ball Run]], the main antagonist, the president of the United States, is named Funny Valentine. The series is known for its many references to pop culture, particularly with regards to music, making this a reference to the song.\n* In ''[[The Good Cop (American TV series)|The Good Cop]]'' Season 1 episode ''Did the TV Star Do It?'', Tony Caruso Sr., played by [[Tony Danza]] starts to sing \"My Funny Valentine\" on TV, but the murderer/TV host pretends to be offended by what he claims are the misogynistic lyrics.  He then fires Tony Sr, allowing him to claim Tony Jr. is out for revenge when he arrests the murderer.\n*In the 1998 anime series directed by Shinichiro Watanabe [[Cowboy Bebop]] the main character Faye Valentine's name is directly attributed to the song.\n*In the 1995 Season 2 Episode of \"Living Single, entitled \"Singing the Blues\" Kyle Barker (T.C Carson) Sings \"My Funny Valentine\" to his on again/ off again rival and lover Max [Maxine Shaw (Erika Alexander) in an attempt to regain his confidence after an earlier performance was derailed by her presence. She is left swooning by the end of the number. In 2015 he covered the song on a single.\n* The song was used in ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' episode Engagement.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of 1930s jazz standards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web |last=Bragalini |first=Luca |year=1997 |title=My Funny Valentine: The Disintegration of the Standard |url=http://www.plosin.com/milesAhead/Valentine.html |publisher=Originally published in Musica Jazz}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Cook |first=Richard |date=1999-02-12 |title=The Hart of the Matter |journal=New Statesman |volume=128 |issue=4423 |page=45 |issn=1364-7431}}\n* {{cite book |last=Fox |first=Dan |year=2007 |title=World's Greatest Wedding Music: 50 of the Most Requested Wedding Pieces |publisher=Alfred Music Publishing |isbn=0-7390-4674-8 |page=}}\n* {{cite book |last=Friedwald |first=Will |authorlink=Will Friedwald |year=2002 |chapter=My Funny Valentine (1937) |title=Stardust Memories: The Biography of Twelve of America's Most Popular Songs |location=New York |publisher=Random House, Inc |isbn=0-375-42089-4 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/stardustmelodies00frie/page/348 348\u2013373] |url=https://archive.org/details/stardustmelodies00frie/page/348 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Gabbard |first=Krin |year=2004 |title=Black Magic: White Hollywood and African American Culture |url=https://archive.org/details/blackmagicwhiteh0000gabb |url-access=registration |publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=0-8135-3384-8 |page=}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hischak |first=Thomas S.|year=2007 |title=The Rodgers and Hammerstein Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood Press |isbn=0-313-34140-0|page=189}}\n* {{cite book |last=Holbrook |first=Morris B. |editors=Steve Lannin and Matthew Caley |year=2005 |chapter=The Ambi-Diegesis of \"My Funny Valentine\" |title=Pop fiction: The Song in Cinema |isbn=1-84150-078-X |location=Portland, OR |publisher=Intellect Books |pages=48\u201362}}\n* {{cite book |last=Studwell |first=William Emmett |year=1994 |title=The Popular Song Reader: A Sampler of Well-Known Twentieth Century-Songs |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1-56024-369-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/popularsongreade0000stud/page/127 127] |url=https://archive.org/details/popularsongreade0000stud/page/127 }}\n\n