{"title_page": "Energy policy of Turkey", "text_new": "{{short description|What the Eurasian country does about coal, gas and electricity}}\n{{About|policy|an overview|Energy in Turkey}}\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Policy and regulation}}\n\nThe [[energy policy]] of [[Turkey]] is to secure [[energy in Turkey|national energy]] supply<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and reduce imports,<ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web |title=TURKEY'S ENERGY PROFILE AND STRATEGY |url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkeys-energy-strategy.en.mfa |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)]] |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> as in the 2010s [[fossil fuel]] costs were<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordenergy.org/wpcms/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2-gas-in-Europe-is-here-who-will-blink-first.pdf|title=$2 gas in Europe is here: who will blink first?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a large part of [[Economy of Turkey#External_trade_and_investment|Turkey's import bill]].<ref name=\"TurkStream\">{{cite web|url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/turkstream_report_eng.pdf|title=TURKSTREAM IMPACT ON TURKEY'S ECONOMY AND ENERGY SECURITY|publisher=\"Istanbul Economics\" & \"The Center for Economics and Foreign Policy\" - EDAM|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> This includes [[Efficient energy use|using energy efficiently]]. However, {{As of|2019||lc=y}}, little research has been done on the policies Turkey uses to reduce [[energy poverty]], which also include some subsidies for home heating and electricity use.<ref name=\":1\" /> The energy strategy includes \"within the context of sustainable development, giving due consideration to environmental concerns all along the energy chain\".<ref name=\"MFA\" /> Turkey's energy policy has been criticized for not looking much beyond 2023,<ref name=\"CAP\">{{cite web |title=How Turkey Can Ensure a Successful Energy Transition |url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition |publisher=Center for American Progress |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> not sufficiently involving the private sector,<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's foreign and security policy 'needs to support its energy goals' |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkeys-foreign-and-security-policy-needs-to-back-its-energy-goals-129628 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> and for being inconsistent with [[climate change in Turkey|Turkey's climate policy]].<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/neighbourhood-enlargement/sites/near/files/20180417-turkey-report.pdf Turkey 2018 Report p92], European Commission, 17 April 2018</ref> \n\n==Security of supply==\n{{See also|Economy of Turkey#Energy security}}\n[[File:Renewable energy reduces fossil fuel imports to Turkey.jpg|thumb|More renewable energy would reduce fossil fuel imports to Turkey]]\nTurkey meets a quarter of its energy demand from national resources.<ref name=\":2\" /> But, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, the country is almost 40% fossil fuel [[Energy independence|energy dependant]] on Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/opinion/barcin-yinanc/a-cost-benefit-analysis-of-idlib-for-turkey-and-russia-152396|title=A cost-benefit analysis of Idlib for Turkey and Russia|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In the 2010s fossil fuel imports were probably the biggest structural vulnerability of the country's economy:<ref name=\"TurkStream\" /> they cost $41 billion in 2019, about a fifth of the total import bill,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/02/06/turkeys-energy-imports-fall-42-in-2019|title=Turkey's energy import bill falls more than 4% in 2019|date=2020-02-06|newspaper=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> and were a large part of the 2018 current account deficit<ref>{{cite web |title=Coal Power Plants |url=https://www.coalinturkey.com/coal-power-plants/ |website=Coal in Turkey |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref> and [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|debt problems]].\n\nTo secure energy supply the government is building new gas pipelines,<ref name=\"TurkStream\" /> and diversifying energy sources. {{As of|2020}} there is a surplus of electricity generation capacity,<ref>Europe Beyond Coal(2020), page 15</ref> however the government aims at meeting the forecast  increase in demand for [[Electricity sector in Turkey|electricity in Turkey]] by building the first [[nuclear power in Turkey|nuclear power plant in Turkey]] and more [[solar power in Turkey|solar]], [[wind power in Turkey|wind]], [[hydroelectricity in Turkey|hydro]] and [[coal in Turkey|coal-fired]] power plants.<ref name=Bayraktar2018>{{cite news |last=BAYRAKTAR |first=ALPARSLAN|title=Analysis: Energy transition in Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/analysis-energy-transition-in-turkey-139413 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |date=4 December 2018}}</ref> As an oil and gas importer Turkey can increase security of supply by increasing the proportion of renewable electricity.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cobenefits.info/|title=COBENEFITS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The [[International Energy Agency]] has suggested that Turkey implement a [[Carbon emission trading|carbon market]].<ref name=\"TPQ2018\" /> In the long term a [[carbon tax]] would reduce import dependency by speeding development of national solar and wind energy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bavbek |first1=G\u00f6k\u015fin |title=Assessing the Potential Efects of a Carbon Tax in Turkey |page=9|url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |website=EDAM Energy and Climate Change Climate Action Paper Series 2016/6 |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause [[Government of Turkey|government in Turkey]] is very centralised energy policy is a national policy. However at certain times of year the east generates excess electricity as it has most [[hydroelectricity in Turkey]], but far less industry and population than the west. This was part of the cause of the [[2015 Turkey blackout|nationwide blackout in 2015]] and therefore policy includes improving electricity transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.power-technology.com/news/ebrd-electricity-network-expansion-turkey/|title=EBRD to finance electricity distribution network expansion in Turkey|date=2019-12-20|website=Power Technology {{!}} Energy News and Market Analysis|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>As well as natural gas storage and [[regasification]] plants,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/02/11/number-of-licenses-issued-for-gas-exports-from-turkey-reaches-18|title=Number of licenses issued for gas exports from Turkey reaches 18|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|date=2020-02-11|work=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> the government supports [[pumped-storage hydroelectricity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/finance/turkey-china-us-to-build-pumped-storage-hydro-plant/28929|title=Turkey, China, US to build pumped-storage hydro plant|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Energy efficiency==\nDespite the Energy Efficiency Law and target to reduce [[energy intensity]] by at least 20 percent between 2011 and 2023; between 2005 and 2015 Turkey's energy intensity increased by 7 percent.<ref name=TPQ2018>{{cite web |title=A NEW STRATEGY FOR EU-TURKEY ENERGY COOPERATION |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly|date=27 November 2018}}</ref> According to one study if energy policy was changed, most importantly to remove fossil fuel subsidies, at least 20% of energy could be saved in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifri.org/sites/default/files/atoms/files/sever_mediterranean_renewables_2019.pdf|title=Accelerating the Energy Transition in the Southern Mediterranean|last=Sever|first=S. Duygu|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Energy Minister Fatih D\u00f6nmez said in 2019 that improvement of public buildings should take the lead and that efficiency improvements are an important source of jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/12/08/energy-efficiency-to-raise-savings-in-public-sector|title=Energy efficiency to raise savings in public sector|date=2019-12-08|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref>\n\n==Fossil fuel subsidies and taxes==\nIn the 21st century fossil fuel subsidies are around 0.2% of GDP,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Fossil fuel subsidies as a lose-lose: Fiscal and environmental burdens in Turkey |journal=New Perspectives on Turkey |volume=58 |pages=93\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/npt.2018.7 |year=2018 |last1=Acar |first1=Sevil |last2=Challe |first2=Sarah |last3=Christopoulos |first3=Stamatios |last4=Christo |first4=Giovanna }}</ref> including US$1.6 billion annually between 2015 and 2017.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey\u2019s energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The energy minister Fatih D\u00f6nmez supports coal<ref>{{cite news |title=Analysis: New Turkish energy minister bullish for coal -- but lira weakness limits market |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/071218-analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-for-coal-but-lira-weakness-limits-market |publisher=S & P Global |date=12 Jul 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Court says 'environment report necessary' for planned coal mine in western Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |agency=Demir\u00f6ren News Agency |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> and most [[Energy subsidies#Turkey|energy subsidies]] are to coal,<ref name=OECD>[http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR \"Fossil Fuel Support - TUR\"], [[OECD]], accessed August 2018.</ref> which has been strongly criticised by the [[OECD]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/sites/058ca239-en/index.html?itemId=/content/publication/058ca239-en&_csp_=733ba7b0813af580090c8c6aac25027b&itemIGO=oecd&itemContentType=book#section-d1e169|title=Taxing Energy Use 2019 : Using Taxes for Climate Action|last=|first=|date=|website=[[OECD]]|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Capacity mechanism payments to [[List of active coal fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] in 2019 totalled 720 million [[Turkish lira|lira]] and to gas-fired [[List of power stations in Turkey|power stations in Turkey]] 542 million lira.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/2019da-40-santrale-1-6-milyar-lira-destek-35998h.htm|title=Kapasite mekanizmas\u0131yla 2019\u2019da 40 santrale 1.6 milyar lira \u00f6dendi|date=2020-02-06|publisher=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr}}</ref>\n{{As of|2018|}} the tax per unit energy on gasoline was higher than diesel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/tax/tax-policy/taxing-energy-use-turkey.pdf|title=Taxing Energy Use 2019: Country Note \u2013 Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[OECD]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> despite diesel cars on average emitting more lung damaging [[NOx]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Leggett|first=Theo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-42666596|title=Reality Check: Are diesel cars always the most harmful?|date=2018-01-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> The price of residential gas and electricity is set by the government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erdo\u011fan announces discounts on residence electricity and natural gas prices ahead of Turkey's elections |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/erdogan-announces-discounts-on-residence-electricity-and-natural-gas-prices-ahead-of-elections-140004 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Natural Gas oligopoly===\nThe purpose of the [[Electricity market#Capacity market|capacity market for electricity]] is claimed to be to secure supply: however despite almost all natural gas being imported some gas-fired power plants received capacity payments in 2019 whereas some non-fossil [[firm service|firm power]] such as [[demand response]] could not.<ref name=capacitymech>[http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2018/01/20180120-23.htm \"ELEKTR\u0130K P\u0130YASASI KAPAS\u0130TE MEKAN\u0130ZMASI Y\u00d6NETMEL\u0130\u011e\u0130,\"] Resm\u00ee Gazete Issue:30307 Article 1 and Article 6 clause 2) h), 20 Jan 2018</ref>\nState-owned [[BOTA\u015e]] controls 80% of the natural gas market and thus the price,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.botas.gov.tr/Sayfa/satis-fiyat-tarifesi/439|title=Sat\u0131\u015f Fiyat Tarifesi {{!}} BOTA\u015e - Boru Hatlar\u0131 \u0130le Petrol Ta\u015f\u0131ma Anonim \u015eirketi|website=www.botas.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> and due to the many sources of supply in the region and [[liquefied natural gas]] from overseas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/commentary/article/the-lng-moment-how-us-production-could-change-more-than-just-markets/|title=The LNG moment: How US production could change more than just markets|date=2019-04-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> wholesale prices in USD are forecast to remain stable or decrease in the long-term.<ref>{{cite news |title=Supply diversity, optimal prices lucrative for Turkey's energy demand |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/03/12/supply-diversity-optimal-prices-lucrative-for-turkeys-energy-demand |work=Daily Sabah |date=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who Will Feed The LNG Monster? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rrapier/2019/02/06/who-will-feed-the-lng-monster/#1b55d2026a4e |work=Forbes |date=6 February 2019}}</ref> However the wholesale gas market is not as competitive as in the EU, as Turkey does not want to split up BOTA\u015e or give other [[List of power companies of Turkey|power companies in Turkey]] fair use of BOTA\u015e\u2019 pipelines, so has not joined [[ENTSO-G]].<ref name=TPQ2018/>\nTurkey's long-term contracts with all its current suppliers \u2013Russia, Azerbaijan and Iran\u2013 are due to expire in the 2020s.<ref name=\"TurkStream\" />\nExploration for gas in the Eastern Mediterranean is subsidized<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey to continue gas drilling work around Cyprus: Foreign minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-continue-gas-drilling-work-around-cyprus-foreign-minister-137940 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"OECD\" /> and is a cause of geopolitical tension due to the [[Cyprus dispute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arbitrationblog.practicallaw.com/what-lies-beneath-gas-pricing-disputes-and-recent-events-in-southern-europe/|title=What lies beneath: gas-pricing disputes and recent events in Southern Europe|last=Lawless|first=Ghislaine|date=2020-02-24|website=Arbitration Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===Coal subsidies===\n[[File:Free coal distributed to poor people by the Family and Social Policies Ministry of Turkey.JPG|thumb|Free coal is distributed to the poor by the [[Ministry of Family and Social Policy (Turkey)|Ministry of Family and Social Policy]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://haberport.com/yasam/2020-sosyal-yardimlasma-komur-yardimi-nasil-alinir-komur-yardimi-basvuru-sartlari-ve-islemleri-h30086.html|title=2020 Sosyal yard\u0131mla\u015fma k\u00f6m\u00fcr yard\u0131m\u0131 nas\u0131l al\u0131n\u0131r? K\u00f6m\u00fcr yard\u0131m\u0131 ba\u015fvuru \u015fartlar\u0131 ve i\u015flemleri|date=3 March 2020|publisher=Haber Port|language=tr}}</ref>]]\n\n[[Coal in Turkey]] is heavily subsidized.<ref>\u015eahin (2018), p. 37</ref> {{As of|2019}} the government aims to keep the share of coal in the energy portfolio at around the same level in the medium to long term.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}} The place of coal in the government's energy policy was detailed in 2019 by the [[Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research]] (SETA), Turkey's lobbying organisation.<ref>{{cite web |title=YERL\u0130 VE M\u0130LL\u0130 ENERJ\u0130 POL\u0130T\u0130KALARI EKSEN\u0130NDE K\u00d6M\u00dcR |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=SETAV |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>  Despite protests against coal power plants<ref>{{cite web|title=Protest against coal power at Sirnak (Turkish)|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/turkey/tr/news/sirnaklilardan-enerji-bakanina-mesaj-020214/}}</ref> [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station|Af\u015fin-Elibistan C]] is being constructed by [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Turkey's state owned generator]] and [[Emba Hunutlu power station|Emba Hunutlu]] with Chinese finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.banktrack.org/project/emba_hunutlu_coal_power_plant|title=Emba Hunutlu coal power plant|website=Banktrack|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Even in cities where natural gas is available the government supports poor households with free coal.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Finance==\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Economics and finance}}\n[[File:Renewable energy increases industrial production in Turkey.jpg|thumb|Renewable energy increases industrial production in Turkey]]\n[[File:Renewable energy increases employment in Turkey.jpg|thumb|Renewable energy increases employment in Turkey]]\n{{as of|2018}} for residential consumers \u201dhigh cost is the most important problem of Turkey\u2019s energy system\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voters in Turkey keep energy policy in mind when voting: Survey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/voters-keep-energy-policy-in-mind-when-voting-survey-142016 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=19 March 2019}}</ref> Europe supports energy efficiency and renewable energy via the 1 billion euro Mid-size Sustainable Energy Financing Facility (MidSEFF).<ref name=TPQ2018/> Up to 150kWh per month free electricity is provided to 2 million poor families.<ref>{{cite news |title=2 milyon 22 bin ailenin 80 liraya kadar elektrik faturas\u0131n\u0131 devlet \u00f6deyecek |url=http://www.diken.com.tr/1-martta-basliyor-2-milyon-22-bin-ailenin-80-liraya-kadar-faturasini-devlet-odeyecek/ |work=Diken |date=28 February 2019}}</ref> [[Fatih Birol]], the head of the [[International Energy Agency]] said in 2019 that, because of its falling price, the focus should be on maximizing onshore [[wind power in Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/12/30/iea-head-turkey-could-benefit-from-energy-resource-glut-in-upcoming-period|title=IEA head: Turkey could benefit from energy resource glut in upcoming period|last=sabah|first=daily|date=2019-12-30|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> The economics of coal power have been modelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Global_Coal_Methodology_Vwebsite2.pdf|title=GLOBAL COAL POWER ECONOMICS MODEL METHODOLOGY|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by [[Carbon Tracker]] and they calculate that by 2020, both new wind and solar power were cheaper than building new coal power plants; and they forecast that wind will become cheaper than existing coal plants in 2027, and solar in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|title=WIND VS COAL POWER IN TURKEY/SOLAR PV VS COAL IN TURKEY|last=|first=|date=2020|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Politics ==\nWithout subsidies new and some existing coal power would be unprofitable, and it is claimed that [[path dependence]], political influence, and distorted markets are what is keeping it going.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2020/3/14/21177941/climate-change-coal-renewable-energy|title=4 astonishing signs of coal\u2019s declining economic viability|last=Roberts|first=David|date=2020-03-14|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Although the coal industry and the government are said to have a close relationship, [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|economic downturn]] and the falling cost of wind and solar may increase pressure on coal subsidies.<ref>{{cite document |last1=Sencan |first1=Gokce |title=Political Reasoning and Mechanisms behind Turkey's Coal-Intensive Energy Policy in the Era of Renewables |publisher=University of California, Santa Barbara |date=2017 |doi=10.13140/RG.2.2.24500.86407 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/314827361}}</ref> Future import of gas from [[Northern Iraq]] may depend on relationships with the [[Kurdistan Regional Government|KRG]], the central government of [[Iraq]] and [[Rosneft]].<ref name=TPQ2018a>{{cite web |title=TURKEY AND THE KURDISTAN REGION OF IRAQ: STRAINED ENERGY RELATIONS |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/937/turkey-and-the-kurdistan-region-of-iraq-strained-energy-relations |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly|date=27 November 2018}}</ref> Hydroelectric plants, especially new ones, are sometimes controversial in local, international and environmental politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eren |first1=Ay\u015fen |title=Transformation of the water-energy nexus in Turkey: Re-imagining hydroelectricity infrastructure |journal=Energy Research & Social Science |date=July 2018 |volume=41 |pages=22\u201331 |doi=10.1016/j.erss.2018.04.013 }}</ref> The EU might be able to persuade Turkey to cooperate on climate change by supporting policies that reduce the country's external energy dependency in a sustainable manner.<ref name=TPQ2018/>\n\nState energy companies include: Eti Mine, [[Turkish Coal Enterprises]], [[Turkish Hard Coal Enterprises]], the [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Electricity Generation Company]], BOTA\u015e and TE\u0130A\u015e - the electricity trading and transmission company.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's state energy companies to invest $1.5B in 2019 |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/18/turkeys-state-energy-companies-to-invest-15b-in-2019 |work=Daily Sabah |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> The government holds a quarter of total installed electricity supply and often offers prices below market levels.<ref name=Reuters2018>{{cite news |last1=Pamuk |first1=Humeyra |title=Once darling of foreign investors, Turkey's power market struggles |url=https://in.mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idINKCN1LQ1S3 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Energy transition==\n{{See also|Nuclear energy in Turkey|Renewable energy in Turkey}} \n\nNuclear safety regulations and human resources could be improved<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edam.org.tr/en/managing-the-risks-of-nuclear-energy-the-turkish-case/|title=Managing the Risks of Nuclear Energy: The Turkish Case|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> by cooperation with [[Euratom]].<ref name=TPQ2018/> In 2018 a new regulator was set up and  $0.15 per kWh of generated electricity will be set aside for waste management.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey sets up new nuclear regulator |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsturkey-sets-up-new-nuclear-regulator-6244883 |work=Nuclear Engineering International |date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA plan for [[solar power in Turkey]] beyond 2023 is needed<ref name=\"Shura2019\">{{cite web |title=Lessons from global experiences for accelerating energy transition in Turkey through solar and wind power |url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/SHURA_Lessons-From-Global-Experiences-for-Accelerating-Energy-Transition-in-Turkey-Through-Solar-and-Wind-Power_Full-Report.pdf |publisher=Shura |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> and amending regulations on rooftop solar panels has been suggested to simplify installation on existing buildings and mandate for new buildings.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), page 44</ref>\n\nIn an attempt to reduce fossil fuel imports [[TOGG Turkish national car|local production of electric cars]] and establishing [[solar cell]] factories is supported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-to-start-local-solar-cell-production-on-june-15/1764779|title=Turkey to start local solar cell production on June 15|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Health and environment==\n{{main|Air pollution in Turkey|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey|Climate change in Turkey}}\n\nRetrofitting equipment for pollution control such as [[flue-gas desulfurization]], at old lignite-fuelled plants such as [[Soma power station|Soma]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Continuing Investments |url=http://www.konyaseker.com.tr/en/icerik/yatirimlarimiz/6598/Our%20Continuing%20Investments |publisher=Konya \u015eeker |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> might not be financially possible, as they use outdated technology.<ref name=\"tepav\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tepav.org.tr/upload/files/haber/1427475571-5.Turkey___s_Compliance_with_the_Industrial_Emissions_Directive.pdf|title=Turkey's Compliance with the Industrial Emissions Directive|publisher=tepav|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> Data on [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]], [[NOx|NO<sub>x</sub>]] and [[particulate]] air pollution from each large plant is collected by government<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hatipoglu |first1=Hakan |title=Inventory of LCPs in Turkey LCP Database explained and explored |url=https://byt.cevre.gov.tr/Pictures/Files/Editor/document/October%202015/1.5%20-%20Hakan%20-%20LCP%20Database%20-%20EN.pdf |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> but not published.\n\nThe energy policy aim of reducing imports (e.g. of gas) conflicts with the climate change policy aim of reducing emission of greenhouse gases as some local resources (e.g. lignite) emit a lot of {{CO2}}. According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey must abandon fossil fuel completely and switch to [[100% renewable energy]] by 2050.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 30</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Coal in Turkey#History}}\nDuring the late 20th and early 21st centuries the country was very exposed to oil and gas price volatility.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/countries/Turkey|title=Turkey - Countries & Regions|website=IEA|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> However around the turn of the century many gas fired power plants were built, and BOTA\u015e extended the national gas pipeline network to most of the urban population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.botas.gov.tr/uploads/galeri/794172-strplan201519_tr.pdf|title=BOTA\u015e strategic plan 2015-2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As Turkey has almost no natural gas of its own this increased import dependancy, particularly on Russian gas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/08/turkstream-europe-needs-gas-and-russia-has-it-the-story-behind-that-new-pipeline|title=Europe needs gas and Russia has it - the story behind the new pipeline|last=Bauomy|first=Jasmin|date=2020-01-08|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Therefore many more regasification plants and gas storage (such as the [[Lake Tuz Natural Gas Storage|gas storage at Lake Tuz]]) were built in the early 21st century, thus ensuring a much longer buffer should the main international import pipelines be cut for any reason. However [[Electricity sector in Turkey#Demand_Forecasts|growth in Turkish electricity demand]] has often been overestimated. Although much energy infrastructure was privatised in the late 20th and early 21st centuries, {{As of|2020||lc=y}}, energy remained highly state controlled.<ref name=\":3\" /> The [[nuclear power debate]] has a long history, with the 2018 construction start at [[Akkuyu Nuclear Power Plant|Akkuyu]] being the sixth major attempt to build a nuclear power plant since 1960.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ayd\u0131n|first=Cem \u0130skender|date=2020-01-01|title=Nuclear energy debate in Turkey: Stakeholders, policy alternatives, and governance issues|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519306287|journal=Energy Policy|language=en|volume=136|pages=111041|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2019.111041|issn=0301-4215}}</ref>\n\n== External resources ==\n* [https://www.epdk.org.tr/Home/En Energy Market Regulatory Authority]\n* [https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/ Istanbul International Centre for Energy and Climate at Sabanc\u0131 University]\n* [https://www.iea.org/countries/turkey Turkey [[International Energy Agency]]]\n* [http://www.worldenergy.org.tr/electricity-market-in-turkey-and-administrative-sanctions-mehmet-ibis/ Electricity Market in Turkey and Administrative Sanctions (in Turkish)]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Environmental issues in Turkey]]\n{{Portal|Turkey|Energy}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite web\n |last=A\u015f\u0131c\u0131\n |first=Ahmet At\u0131l\n |date=May 2017\n |title=Climate friendly Green Economy Policies\n |work=Istanbul Policy Center \n |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/GreenEconomyPolicies.pdf  \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |last=\u015eahin\n |first=\u00dcmit \n |date=February 2018 \n |title=Carbon Lock-In in Turkey: A Comparative Perspective of Low-Carbon Transition with Germany and Poland\n |work=Istanbul Policy Center \n |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/CarbonLockin_%C5%9Eahin_ENG.pdf  \n }}\n\n*{{cite book\n|ref=Sar\u0131&Sayg\u0131n\n|last=Sar\u0131 \n|first=Ay\u015fe Ceren and De\u011fer Sayg\u0131n \n|title=On the way to efficiently supplying more than half of Turkey's electricity from renewables: Opportunities to strengthen the YEKA auction model for enhancing the regulatory framework of Turkey\u00b4s power system transformation\n|publisher=SHURA Energy Transition Center \n|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/SHURA_Opportunities-to-strengthen-the-YEKA-auction-model-for-enhancing-the-regulatory-framework-of-Turkeys-power-system.pdf  \n|year=2018\n|isbn= 978-605-2095-44-7 \n}}\n\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the technical review of the seventh national communication of Turkey\n |date=June 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/idr7_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|Tech review 7th communication|2019}}\n }}\n\n*{{Cite magazine\n |last1=\u015eahin\n |first1=\u00dcmit\n |last2=T\u00fcrkkan\n |first2=Se\u00e7il\n |date=January 2019\n |title=TURKEY\u2019S CLIMATE POLICIES HAVE REACHED A DEADLOCK: IT TAKES COURAGE TO RESOLVE IT\n |url=https://www.hyd.org.tr/attachments/article/511/saha2en.pdf\n |magazine=saha\n |volume=Special Issue 2\n |pages=24\u201330\n |issn=2149-7885}}\n\n*{{cite report\n |date         = January 2020 \n |title        = E\u00dcA\u015e - A briefing for investors, insurers and banks\n |publisher    = [[Beyond Coal|Europe Beyond Coal]]\n |url          = https://beyond-coal.eu/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/EBC_EUAS_briefing-paper.pdf\n}}\n\n\n[[Category:Energy policy by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy policy in Asia|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy policy in Europe|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy law]]\n[[Category:Climate change in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|What the Eurasian country does about coal, gas and electricity}}\n{{About|policy|an overview|Energy in Turkey}}\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Policy and regulation}}\n\nThe [[energy policy]] of [[Turkey]] is to secure [[energy in Turkey|national energy]] supply<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and reduce imports,<ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web |title=TURKEY'S ENERGY PROFILE AND STRATEGY |url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkeys-energy-strategy.en.mfa |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)]] |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> as in the 2010s [[fossil fuel]] costs were<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordenergy.org/wpcms/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2-gas-in-Europe-is-here-who-will-blink-first.pdf|title=$2 gas in Europe is here: who will blink first?|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a large part of [[Economy of Turkey#External_trade_and_investment|Turkey's import bill]].<ref name=\"TurkStream\">{{cite web|url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/turkstream_report_eng.pdf|title=TURKSTREAM IMPACT ON TURKEY'S ECONOMY AND ENERGY SECURITY|publisher=\"Istanbul Economics\" & \"The Center for Economics and Foreign Policy\" - EDAM|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> This includes [[Efficient energy use|using energy efficiently]]. However, {{As of|2019||lc=y}}, little research has been done on the policies Turkey uses to reduce [[energy poverty]], which also include some subsidies for home heating and electricity use.<ref name=\":1\" /> The energy strategy includes \"within the context of sustainable development, giving due consideration to environmental concerns all along the energy chain\".<ref name=\"MFA\" /> Turkey's energy policy has been criticized for not looking much beyond 2023,<ref name=\"CAP\">{{cite web |title=How Turkey Can Ensure a Successful Energy Transition |url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition |publisher=Center for American Progress |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> not sufficiently involving the private sector,<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's foreign and security policy 'needs to support its energy goals' |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkeys-foreign-and-security-policy-needs-to-back-its-energy-goals-129628 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> and for being inconsistent with [[climate change in Turkey|Turkey's climate policy]].<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/neighbourhood-enlargement/sites/near/files/20180417-turkey-report.pdf Turkey 2018 Report p92], European Commission, 17 April 2018</ref> \n\n==Security of supply==\n{{See also|Economy of Turkey#Energy security}}\n[[File:Renewable energy reduces fossil fuel imports to Turkey.jpg|thumb|More renewable energy would reduce fossil fuel imports to Turkey]]\nTurkey meets a quarter of its energy demand from national resources.<ref name=\":2\" /> But, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, the country is almost 40% fossil fuel [[Energy independence|energy dependant]] on Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/opinion/barcin-yinanc/a-cost-benefit-analysis-of-idlib-for-turkey-and-russia-152396|title=A cost-benefit analysis of Idlib for Turkey and Russia|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In the 2010s fossil fuel imports were probably the biggest structural vulnerability of the country's economy:<ref name=\"TurkStream\" /> they cost $41 billion in 2019, about a fifth of the total import bill,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/02/06/turkeys-energy-imports-fall-42-in-2019|title=Turkey's energy import bill falls more than 4% in 2019|date=2020-02-06|newspaper=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> and were a large part of the 2018 current account deficit<ref>{{cite web |title=Coal Power Plants |url=https://www.coalinturkey.com/coal-power-plants/ |website=Coal in Turkey |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref> and [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|debt problems]].\n\nTo secure energy supply the government is building new gas pipelines,<ref name=\"TurkStream\" /> and diversifying energy sources. {{As of|2020}} there is a surplus of electricity generation capacity,<ref>Europe Beyond Coal(2020), page 15</ref> however the government aims at meeting the forecast  increase in demand for [[Electricity sector in Turkey|electricity in Turkey]] by building the first [[nuclear power in Turkey|nuclear power plant in Turkey]] and more [[solar power in Turkey|solar]], [[wind power in Turkey|wind]], [[hydroelectricity in Turkey|hydro]] and [[coal in Turkey|coal-fired]] power plants.<ref name=Bayraktar2018>{{cite news |last=BAYRAKTAR |first=ALPARSLAN|title=Analysis: Energy transition in Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/analysis-energy-transition-in-turkey-139413 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |date=4 December 2018}}</ref> As an oil and gas importer Turkey can increase security of supply by increasing the proportion of renewable electricity.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cobenefits.info/|title=COBENEFITS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The [[International Energy Agency]] has suggested that Turkey implement a [[Carbon emission trading|carbon market]].<ref name=\"TPQ2018\" /> In the long term a [[carbon tax]] would reduce import dependency by speeding development of national solar and wind energy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bavbek |first1=G\u00f6k\u015fin |title=Assessing the Potential Efects of a Carbon Tax in Turkey |page=9|url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |website=EDAM Energy and Climate Change Climate Action Paper Series 2016/6 |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nBecause [[Government of Turkey|government in Turkey]] is very centralised energy policy is a national policy. However at certain times of year the east generates excess electricity as it has most [[hydroelectricity in Turkey]], but far less industry and population than the west. This was part of the cause of the [[2015 Turkey blackout|nationwide blackout in 2015]] and therefore policy includes improving electricity transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.power-technology.com/news/ebrd-electricity-network-expansion-turkey/|title=EBRD to finance electricity distribution network expansion in Turkey|date=2019-12-20|website=Power Technology {{!}} Energy News and Market Analysis|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>As well as natural gas storage and [[regasification]] plants,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/02/11/number-of-licenses-issued-for-gas-exports-from-turkey-reaches-18|title=Number of licenses issued for gas exports from Turkey reaches 18|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|date=2020-02-11|work=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> the government supports [[pumped-storage hydroelectricity]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/finance/turkey-china-us-to-build-pumped-storage-hydro-plant/28929|title=Turkey, China, US to build pumped-storage hydro plant|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Energy efficiency==\nDespite the Energy Efficiency Law and target to reduce [[energy intensity]] by at least 20 percent between 2011 and 2023; between 2005 and 2015 Turkey's energy intensity increased by 7 percent.<ref name=TPQ2018>{{cite web |title=A NEW STRATEGY FOR EU-TURKEY ENERGY COOPERATION |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly|date=27 November 2018}}</ref> According to one study if energy policy was changed, most importantly to remove fossil fuel subsidies, at least 20% of energy could be saved in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifri.org/sites/default/files/atoms/files/sever_mediterranean_renewables_2019.pdf|title=Accelerating the Energy Transition in the Southern Mediterranean|last=Sever|first=S. Duygu|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Energy Minister Fatih D\u00f6nmez said in 2019 that improvement of public buildings should take the lead and that efficiency improvements are an important source of jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/12/08/energy-efficiency-to-raise-savings-in-public-sector|title=Energy efficiency to raise savings in public sector|date=2019-12-08|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref>\n\n==Fossil fuel subsidies and taxes==\nIn the 21st century fossil fuel subsidies are around 0.2% of GDP,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Fossil fuel subsidies as a lose-lose: Fiscal and environmental burdens in Turkey |journal=New Perspectives on Turkey |volume=58 |pages=93\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/npt.2018.7 |year=2018 |last1=Acar |first1=Sevil |last2=Challe |first2=Sarah |last3=Christopoulos |first3=Stamatios |last4=Christo |first4=Giovanna }}</ref> including US$1.6 billion annually between 2015 and 2017.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey\u2019s energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The energy minister Fatih D\u00f6nmez supports coal<ref>{{cite news |title=Analysis: New Turkish energy minister bullish for coal -- but lira weakness limits market |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/071218-analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-for-coal-but-lira-weakness-limits-market |publisher=S & P Global |date=12 Jul 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Court says 'environment report necessary' for planned coal mine in western Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |agency=Demir\u00f6ren News Agency |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> and most [[Energy subsidies#Turkey|energy subsidies]] are to coal,<ref name=OECD>[http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR \"Fossil Fuel Support - TUR\"], [[OECD]], accessed August 2018.</ref> which has been strongly criticised by the [[OECD]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/sites/058ca239-en/index.html?itemId=/content/publication/058ca239-en&_csp_=733ba7b0813af580090c8c6aac25027b&itemIGO=oecd&itemContentType=book#section-d1e169|title=Taxing Energy Use 2019 : Using Taxes for Climate Action|last=|first=|date=|website=[[OECD]]|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Capacity mechanism payments to [[List of active coal fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] in 2019 totalled 720 million [[Turkish lira|lira]] and to gas-fired [[List of power stations in Turkey|power stations in Turkey]] 542 million lira.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/2019da-40-santrale-1-6-milyar-lira-destek-35998h.htm|title=Kapasite mekanizmas\u0131yla 2019\u2019da 40 santrale 1.6 milyar lira \u00f6dendi|date=2020-02-06|publisher=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr}}</ref>\n{{As of|2018|}} the tax per unit energy on gasoline was higher than diesel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/tax/tax-policy/taxing-energy-use-turkey.pdf|title=Taxing Energy Use 2019: Country Note \u2013 Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[OECD]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> despite diesel cars on average emitting more lung damaging [[NOx]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Leggett|first=Theo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-42666596|title=Reality Check: Are diesel cars always the most harmful?|date=2018-01-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> The price of residential gas and electricity is set by the government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erdo\u011fan announces discounts on residence electricity and natural gas prices ahead of Turkey's elections |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/erdogan-announces-discounts-on-residence-electricity-and-natural-gas-prices-ahead-of-elections-140004 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=25 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Natural Gas oligopoly===\nThe purpose of the [[Electricity market#Capacity market|capacity market for electricity]] is claimed to be to secure supply: however despite almost all natural gas being imported some gas-fired power plants received capacity payments in 2019 whereas some non-fossil [[firm service|firm power]] such as [[demand response]] could not.<ref name=capacitymech>[http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2018/01/20180120-23.htm \"ELEKTR\u0130K P\u0130YASASI KAPAS\u0130TE MEKAN\u0130ZMASI Y\u00d6NETMEL\u0130\u011e\u0130,\"] Resm\u00ee Gazete Issue:30307 Article 1 and Article 6 clause 2) h), 20 Jan 2018</ref>\nState-owned [[BOTA\u015e]] controls 80% of the natural gas market and thus the price,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.botas.gov.tr/Sayfa/satis-fiyat-tarifesi/439|title=Sat\u0131\u015f Fiyat Tarifesi {{!}} BOTA\u015e - Boru Hatlar\u0131 \u0130le Petrol Ta\u015f\u0131ma Anonim \u015eirketi|website=www.botas.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> and due to the many sources of supply in the region and [[liquefied natural gas]] from overseas<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/commentary/article/the-lng-moment-how-us-production-could-change-more-than-just-markets/|title=The LNG moment: How US production could change more than just markets|date=2019-04-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> wholesale prices in USD are forecast to remain stable or decrease in the long-term.<ref>{{cite news |title=Supply diversity, optimal prices lucrative for Turkey's energy demand |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/03/12/supply-diversity-optimal-prices-lucrative-for-turkeys-energy-demand |work=Daily Sabah |date=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who Will Feed The LNG Monster? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rrapier/2019/02/06/who-will-feed-the-lng-monster/#1b55d2026a4e |work=Forbes |date=6 February 2019}}</ref> However the wholesale gas market is not as competitive as in the EU, as Turkey does not want to split up BOTA\u015e or give other [[List of power companies of Turkey|power companies in Turkey]] fair use of BOTA\u015e\u2019 pipelines, so has not joined [[ENTSO-G]].<ref name=TPQ2018/>\nTurkey's long-term contracts with all its current suppliers \u2013Russia, Azerbaijan and Iran\u2013 are due to expire in the 2020s.<ref name=\"TurkStream\" />\nExploration for gas in the Eastern Mediterranean is subsidized<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey to continue gas drilling work around Cyprus: Foreign minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-continue-gas-drilling-work-around-cyprus-foreign-minister-137940 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"OECD\" /> and is a cause of geopolitical tension due to the [[Cyprus dispute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arbitrationblog.practicallaw.com/what-lies-beneath-gas-pricing-disputes-and-recent-events-in-southern-europe/|title=What lies beneath: gas-pricing disputes and recent events in Southern Europe|last=Lawless|first=Ghislaine|date=2020-02-24|website=Arbitration Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===Coal subsidies===\n[[File:Free coal distributed to poor people by the Family and Social Policies Ministry of Turkey.JPG|thumb|Free coal is distributed to the poor by the [[Ministry of Family and Social Policy (Turkey)|Ministry of Family and Social Policy]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://haberport.com/yasam/2020-sosyal-yardimlasma-komur-yardimi-nasil-alinir-komur-yardimi-basvuru-sartlari-ve-islemleri-h30086.html|title=2020 Sosyal yard\u0131mla\u015fma k\u00f6m\u00fcr yard\u0131m\u0131 nas\u0131l al\u0131n\u0131r? K\u00f6m\u00fcr yard\u0131m\u0131 ba\u015fvuru \u015fartlar\u0131 ve i\u015flemleri|date=3 March 2020|publisher=Haber Port|language=tr}}</ref>]]\n\n[[Coal in Turkey]] is heavily subsidized.<ref>\u015eahin (2018), p. 37</ref> {{As of|2019}} the government aims to keep the share of coal in the energy portfolio at around the same level in the medium to long term.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}} The place of coal in the government's energy policy was detailed in 2019 by the [[Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research]] (SETA), Turkey's lobbying organisation.<ref>{{cite web |title=YERL\u0130 VE M\u0130LL\u0130 ENERJ\u0130 POL\u0130T\u0130KALARI EKSEN\u0130NDE K\u00d6M\u00dcR |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=SETAV |accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref>  Despite protests against coal power plants<ref>{{cite web|title=Protest against coal power at Sirnak (Turkish)|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/turkey/tr/news/sirnaklilardan-enerji-bakanina-mesaj-020214/}}</ref> [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station|Af\u015fin-Elibistan C]] is being constructed by [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Turkey's state owned generator]] and [[Emba Hunutlu power station|Emba Hunutlu]] with Chinese finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.banktrack.org/project/emba_hunutlu_coal_power_plant|title=Emba Hunutlu coal power plant|website=Banktrack|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Even in cities where natural gas is available the government supports poor households with free coal.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Finance==\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Economics and finance}}\n[[File:Renewable energy increases industrial production in Turkey.jpg|thumb|Renewable energy increases industrial production in Turkey]]\n[[File:Renewable energy increases employment in Turkey.jpg|thumb|Renewable energy increases employment in Turkey]]\n{{as of|2018}} for residential consumers \u201dhigh cost is the most important problem of Turkey\u2019s energy system\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voters in Turkey keep energy policy in mind when voting: Survey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/voters-keep-energy-policy-in-mind-when-voting-survey-142016 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=19 March 2019}}</ref> Europe supports energy efficiency and renewable energy via the 1 billion euro Mid-size Sustainable Energy Financing Facility (MidSEFF).<ref name=TPQ2018/> Up to 150kWh per month free electricity is provided to 2 million poor families.<ref>{{cite news |title=2 milyon 22 bin ailenin 80 liraya kadar elektrik faturas\u0131n\u0131 devlet \u00f6deyecek |url=http://www.diken.com.tr/1-martta-basliyor-2-milyon-22-bin-ailenin-80-liraya-kadar-faturasini-devlet-odeyecek/ |work=Diken |date=28 February 2019}}</ref> [[Fatih Birol]], the head of the [[International Energy Agency]] said in 2019 that, because of its falling price, the focus should be on maximizing onshore [[wind power in Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/12/30/iea-head-turkey-could-benefit-from-energy-resource-glut-in-upcoming-period|title=IEA head: Turkey could benefit from energy resource glut in upcoming period|last=sabah|first=daily|date=2019-12-30|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> The economics of coal power have been modelled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Global_Coal_Methodology_Vwebsite2.pdf|title=GLOBAL COAL POWER ECONOMICS MODEL METHODOLOGY|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> by [[Carbon Tracker]] and they calculate that by 2020, both new wind and solar power were cheaper than building new coal power plants; and they forecast that wind will become cheaper than existing coal plants in 2027, and solar in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|title=WIND VS COAL POWER IN TURKEY/SOLAR PV VS COAL IN TURKEY|last=|first=|date=2020|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Politics ==\nWithout subsidies new and some existing coal power would be unprofitable, and it is claimed that [[path dependence]], political influence, and distorted markets are what is keeping it going.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2020/3/14/21177941/climate-change-coal-renewable-energy|title=4 astonishing signs of coal\u2019s declining economic viability|last=Roberts|first=David|date=2020-03-14|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Although the coal industry and the government are said to have a close relationship, [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|economic downturn]] and the falling cost of wind and solar may increase pressure on coal subsidies.<ref>{{cite document |last1=Sencan |first1=Gokce |title=Political Reasoning and Mechanisms behind Turkey's Coal-Intensive Energy Policy in the Era of Renewables |publisher=University of California, Santa Barbara |date=2017 |doi=10.13140/RG.2.2.24500.86407 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/314827361}}</ref> Future import of gas from [[Northern Iraq]] may depend on relationships with the [[Kurdistan Regional Government|KRG]], the central government of [[Iraq]] and [[Rosneft]].<ref name=TPQ2018a>{{cite web |title=TURKEY AND THE KURDISTAN REGION OF IRAQ: STRAINED ENERGY RELATIONS |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/937/turkey-and-the-kurdistan-region-of-iraq-strained-energy-relations |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly|date=27 November 2018}}</ref> Hydroelectric plants, especially new ones, are sometimes controversial in local, international and environmental politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eren |first1=Ay\u015fen |title=Transformation of the water-energy nexus in Turkey: Re-imagining hydroelectricity infrastructure |journal=Energy Research & Social Science |date=July 2018 |volume=41 |pages=22\u201331 |doi=10.1016/j.erss.2018.04.013 }}</ref> The EU might be able to persuade Turkey to cooperate on climate change by supporting policies that reduce the country's external energy dependency in a sustainable manner.<ref name=TPQ2018/>\n\nState energy companies include: Eti Mine, [[Turkish Coal Enterprises]], [[Turkish Hard Coal Enterprises]], the [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Electricity Generation Company]], BOTA\u015e and TE\u0130A\u015e - the electricity trading and transmission company.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's state energy companies to invest $1.5B in 2019 |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/18/turkeys-state-energy-companies-to-invest-15b-in-2019 |work=Daily Sabah |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> The government holds a quarter of total installed electricity supply and often offers prices below market levels.<ref name=Reuters2018>{{cite news |last1=Pamuk |first1=Humeyra |title=Once darling of foreign investors, Turkey's power market struggles |url=https://in.mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idINKCN1LQ1S3 |accessdate=11 October 2018 |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Energy transition==\n{{See also|Nuclear energy in Turkey|Renewable energy in Turkey}} \n\nNuclear safety regulations and human resources could be improved<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edam.org.tr/en/managing-the-risks-of-nuclear-energy-the-turkish-case/|title=Managing the Risks of Nuclear Energy: The Turkish Case|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> by cooperation with [[Euratom]].<ref name=TPQ2018/> In 2018 a new regulator was set up and  $0.15 per kWh of generated electricity will be set aside for waste management.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey sets up new nuclear regulator |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsturkey-sets-up-new-nuclear-regulator-6244883 |work=Nuclear Engineering International |date=13 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA plan for [[solar power in Turkey]] beyond 2023 is needed<ref name=\"Shura2019\">{{cite web |title=Lessons from global experiences for accelerating energy transition in Turkey through solar and wind power |url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/SHURA_Lessons-From-Global-Experiences-for-Accelerating-Energy-Transition-in-Turkey-Through-Solar-and-Wind-Power_Full-Report.pdf |publisher=Shura |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> and amending regulations on rooftop solar panels has been suggested to simplify installation on existing buildings and mandate for new buildings.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), page 44</ref>\n\nIn an attempt to reduce fossil fuel imports [[TOGG Turkish national car|local production of electric cars]] and establishing [[solar cell]] factories is supported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-to-start-local-solar-cell-production-on-june-15/1764779|title=Turkey to start local solar cell production on June 15|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Health and environment==\n{{main|Air pollution in Turkey|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey|Climate change in Turkey}}\n\nRetrofitting equipment for pollution control such as [[flue-gas desulfurization]], at old lignite-fuelled plants such as [[Soma power station|Soma]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Continuing Investments |url=http://www.konyaseker.com.tr/en/icerik/yatirimlarimiz/6598/Our%20Continuing%20Investments |publisher=Konya \u015eeker |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> might not be financially possible, as they use outdated technology.<ref name=\"tepav\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tepav.org.tr/upload/files/haber/1427475571-5.Turkey___s_Compliance_with_the_Industrial_Emissions_Directive.pdf|title=Turkey's Compliance with the Industrial Emissions Directive|publisher=tepav|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> Data on [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]], [[NOx|NO<sub>x</sub>]] and [[particulate]] air pollution from each large plant is collected by government<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hatipoglu |first1=Hakan |title=Inventory of LCPs in Turkey LCP Database explained and explored |url=https://byt.cevre.gov.tr/Pictures/Files/Editor/document/October%202015/1.5%20-%20Hakan%20-%20LCP%20Database%20-%20EN.pdf |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> but not published.\n\nThe energy policy aim of reducing imports (e.g. of gas) conflicts with the climate change policy aim of reducing emission of greenhouse gases as some local resources (e.g. lignite) emit a lot of {{CO2}}. According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey must abandon fossil fuel completely and switch to [[100% renewable energy]] by 2050.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 30</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Coal in Turkey#History}}\nDuring the late 20th and early 21st centuries the country was very exposed to oil and gas price volatility.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/countries/Turkey|title=Turkey - Countries & Regions|website=IEA|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> However around the turn of the century many gas fired power plants were built, and BOTA\u015e extended the national gas pipeline network to most of the urban population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.botas.gov.tr/uploads/galeri/794172-strplan201519_tr.pdf|title=BOTA\u015e strategic plan 2015-2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As Turkey has almost no natural gas of its own this increased import dependancy, particularly on Russian gas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/08/turkstream-europe-needs-gas-and-russia-has-it-the-story-behind-that-new-pipeline|title=Europe needs gas and Russia has it - the story behind the new pipeline|last=Bauomy|first=Jasmin|date=2020-01-08|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Therefore many more regasification plants and gas storage (such as the [[Lake Tuz Natural Gas Storage|gas storage at Lake Tuz]]) were built in the early 21st century, thus ensuring a much longer buffer should the main international import pipelines be cut for any reason. However [[Electricity sector in Turkey#Demand_Forecasts|growth in Turkish electricity demand]] has often been overestimated. Although much energy infrastructure was privatised in the late 20th and early 21st centuries, {{As of|2020||lc=y}}, energy remained highly state controlled.<ref name=\":3\" /> The [[nuclear power debate]] has a long history, with the 2020s construction of [[Akkuyu Nuclear Power Plant|Akkuyu]] being the sixth major attempt to build a nuclear power plant since 1960.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ayd\u0131n|first=Cem \u0130skender|date=2020-01-01|title=Nuclear energy debate in Turkey: Stakeholders, policy alternatives, and governance issues|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519306287|journal=Energy Policy|language=en|volume=136|pages=111041|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2019.111041|issn=0301-4215}}</ref>\n\n== External resources ==\n* [https://www.epdk.org.tr/Home/En Energy Market Regulatory Authority]\n* [https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/ Istanbul International Centre for Energy and Climate at Sabanc\u0131 University]\n* [https://www.iea.org/countries/turkey Turkey [[International Energy Agency]]]\n* [http://www.worldenergy.org.tr/electricity-market-in-turkey-and-administrative-sanctions-mehmet-ibis/ Electricity Market in Turkey and Administrative Sanctions (in Turkish)]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Environmental issues in Turkey]]\n{{Portal|Turkey|Energy}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*{{cite web\n |last=A\u015f\u0131c\u0131\n |first=Ahmet At\u0131l\n |date=May 2017\n |title=Climate friendly Green Economy Policies\n |work=Istanbul Policy Center \n |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/GreenEconomyPolicies.pdf  \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |last=\u015eahin\n |first=\u00dcmit \n |date=February 2018 \n |title=Carbon Lock-In in Turkey: A Comparative Perspective of Low-Carbon Transition with Germany and Poland\n |work=Istanbul Policy Center \n |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/CarbonLockin_%C5%9Eahin_ENG.pdf  \n }}\n\n*{{cite book\n|ref=Sar\u0131&Sayg\u0131n\n|last=Sar\u0131 \n|first=Ay\u015fe Ceren and De\u011fer Sayg\u0131n \n|title=On the way to efficiently supplying more than half of Turkey's electricity from renewables: Opportunities to strengthen the YEKA auction model for enhancing the regulatory framework of Turkey\u00b4s power system transformation\n|publisher=SHURA Energy Transition Center \n|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/SHURA_Opportunities-to-strengthen-the-YEKA-auction-model-for-enhancing-the-regulatory-framework-of-Turkeys-power-system.pdf  \n|year=2018\n|isbn= 978-605-2095-44-7 \n}}\n\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the technical review of the seventh national communication of Turkey\n |date=June 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/idr7_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|Tech review 7th communication|2019}}\n }}\n\n*{{Cite magazine\n |last1=\u015eahin\n |first1=\u00dcmit\n |last2=T\u00fcrkkan\n |first2=Se\u00e7il\n |date=January 2019\n |title=TURKEY\u2019S CLIMATE POLICIES HAVE REACHED A DEADLOCK: IT TAKES COURAGE TO RESOLVE IT\n |url=https://www.hyd.org.tr/attachments/article/511/saha2en.pdf\n |magazine=saha\n |volume=Special Issue 2\n |pages=24\u201330\n |issn=2149-7885}}\n\n*{{cite report\n |date         = January 2020 \n |title        = E\u00dcA\u015e - A briefing for investors, insurers and banks\n |publisher    = [[Beyond Coal|Europe Beyond Coal]]\n |url          = https://beyond-coal.eu/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/EBC_EUAS_briefing-paper.pdf\n}}\n\n\n[[Category:Energy policy by country|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy policy in Asia|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy policy in Europe|Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Energy law]]\n[[Category:Climate change in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Chidgk1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_policy_of_Turkey"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Napiontek", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Arthur Napiontek|timestamp=20200406104701|year=2020|month=April|day=6|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Arthur Napiontek|date=6 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{One source|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Arthur Michael Napiontek\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|7|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Port Angeles, Washington]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Michael \"Art\" Napiontek''' (born June 23, 1987) is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]],<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://dvd-copy.com/people/Arthur-Napiontek/2433886/bio.htm |title=Bio |accessdate=2012-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907031000/http://dvd-copy.com/people/Arthur-Napiontek/2433886/bio.htm |archivedate=2014-09-07 }}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> [[Model (person)|model]], and [[screenwriter]]. His most notable work to date is ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''. He appeared in an episode of the fifth season of ''[[True Blood]]'' as a member of a fraternity, and this is termed a \"co-starring\" role in the fifth season, which began in 2012.\nAs a model, Napiontek has worked for ''[[Calvin Klein]]''.\nHe has written a screenplay, ''Holy Takedown!'', which is currently in pre-production.\n\n==Early life==\nArthur Napiontek was born on July 23, 1987, in [[Port Angeles, Washington]].<ref name=bio/>\nHe currently lives in [[Los Angeles]]\n\n==Acting==\nArthur's first piece of filmography was ''Nora Breaks Free'' in 2006. In 2007, he was in the [[television movie]] ''Not Another High School Show''. The following year, Napiontek had a brief role as Clark in the high school hallway scene of ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'', sparking jealousy of his looks in [[Seth Rogen]]'s character. \n\nLike ''Nora'' in 2006, Napiontek was in another short entitled ''Boys from the Bar'' in 2011. Napiontek continued to act during this year, making two guest appearances as two different characters on the television series ''[[Greek (TV series)|Greek]]'', first in the episode \"All About Beav\", then in the episode called \"Legacy\".\n\nNapiontek is appear in season five of ''[[True Blood]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Nora Breaks Free''  || 2006 || Gavin (short film)\n|-\n| ''Not Another High School Show'' || 2007 || Chad (TV movie)\n|-\n| ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'' || 2008 || Clark\n|-\n| ''[[The Brotherhood V: Alumni]]'' || 2009 || Ted\n|-\n| ''Boys from the Bar'' || 2011 || Jeff (short film)\n|-\n| ''[[Greek (TV series)|Greek]]'' || 2011 || Football Player #1 in ''All About Beav''; Jock #1 in ''Legacy''\n|-\n| ''[[True Blood]]'' || 2012 || First episode: ''[[Turn! Turn! Turn! (True Blood)|Turn! Turn! Turn!]]'' (Season Five premiere)\n|-\n| ''[[The Best people]]'' || 2017 || Art (co-lead) \n|-\n| ''Geography Now'' || 2020 || Himself (Series regular)  \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2433886}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Napiontek, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Arthur Napiontek|timestamp=20200406104701|year=2020|month=April|day=6|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Arthur Napiontek|date=6 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{One source|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Arthur Michael Napiontek\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|7|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Port Angeles, Washington]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Michael \"Art\" Napiontek''' (born June 23, 1987) is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]],<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://dvd-copy.com/people/Arthur-Napiontek/2433886/bio.htm |title=Bio |accessdate=2012-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907031000/http://dvd-copy.com/people/Arthur-Napiontek/2433886/bio.htm |archivedate=2014-09-07 }}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> [[Model (person)|model]], and [[screenwriter]]. His most notable work to date is ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''. He appeared in an episode of the fifth season of ''[[True Blood]]'' as a member of a fraternity, and this is termed a \"co-starring\" role in the fifth season, which began in 2012.\nAs a model, Napiontek has worked for ''[[Calvin Klein]]''.\nHe has written a screenplay, ''Holy Takedown!'', which is currently in pre-production.\n\n==Early life==\nArthur Napiontek was born on July 23, 1987, in [[Port Angeles, Washington]].<ref name=bio/>\nHe currently lives in [[Los Angeles]]\n\n==Acting==\nArthur's first piece of filmography was ''Nora Breaks Free'' in 2006. In 2007, he was in the [[television movie]] ''Not Another High School Show''. The following year, Napiontek had a brief role as Clark in the high school hallway scene of ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'', sparking jealousy of his looks in [[Seth Rogen]]'s character. \n\nLike ''Nora'' in 2006, Napiontek was in another short entitled ''Boys from the Bar'' in 2011. Napiontek continued to act during this year, making two guest appearances as two different characters on the television series ''[[Greek (TV series)|Greek]]'', first in the episode \"All About Beav\", then in the episode called \"Legacy\".\n\nNapiontek is appear in season five of ''[[True Blood]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Notes\n|-\n| ''Nora Breaks Free''  || 2006 || Gavin (short film)\n|-\n| ''Not Another High School Show'' || 2007 || Chad (TV movie)\n|-\n| ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'' || 2008 || Clark\n|-\n| ''[[The Brotherhood V: Alumni]]'' || 2009 || Ted\n|-\n| ''Boys from the Bar'' || 2011 || Jeff (short film)\n|-\n| ''[[Greek (TV series)|Greek]]'' || 2011 || Football Player #1 in ''All About Beav''; Jock #1 in ''Legacy''\n|-\n| ''[[True Blood]]'' || 2012 || First episode: ''[[Turn! Turn! Turn! (True Blood)|Turn! Turn! Turn!]]'' (Season Five premiere)\n|-\n| ''[[The Best people]]'' || 2017 || Art (co-lead) \n|-\n| ''[[Geography Now]]'' || 2020 || Himself (Series regular)  \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2433886}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Napiontek, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Paul Barbato (2nd nomination)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Napiontek"}
{"title_page": "Keith Critchlow", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Keith Critchlow\n| image              = <!-- Keith Critchlow-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Keith Barry Critchlow\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1933|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2020|4|8|1933|3|16}}\n| death_place        = Kingston-Upon-Thames, London\n| nationality        = UK\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = sacred architecture design and analysis, founder of Visual Islamic and Traditional Arts (VITA) school, co-founder of the [[Temenos Academy]]\n| occupation         = professor of architecture, author\n| alma_mater         = [[Summerhill School]]<br>[[St Martins School of Art]]<br>[[Royal College of Art]]\n}}\n\n'''Keith Barry Critchlow''' (16 March 1933 \u2013 8 April 2020) was an artist, lecturer, author, professor of architecture and a co-founder of the [[Temenos Academy]] in the UK. He was also a leading expert in [[sacred architecture]] and [[sacred geometry]]. \n\n==Biography==\nCritchlow was educated at the [[Summerhill School]], [[Saint Martin's School of Art|St Martins School of Art]], and the [[Royal College of Art]].<ref>[http://www.cosm.org/about/boardofadvisors.html \"Biography: Keith Critchlow\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525134534/http://www.cosm.org/about/boardofadvisors.html |date=25 May 2011 }}, Board of Advisers, [[Alex Grey|Chapel of Sacred Mirrors]], New York.</ref> \n\nWhilst at St Martins he studied alongside renowned artists [[Leon Kossoff]], [[Frank Auerbach]] and [[Joe Tilson]], with whom he developed great friendships and gained much artistic inspiration as a painter. At St Martins, he also met [[Z'ev ben Shimon Halevi]] (born Warren Kenton), who subsequently authored books on the Toledano Tradition of Kabbalah and became a founder member of the Kabbalah Society; they were lifelong friends.\n\nCritchlow performed [[national service]] in the [[Royal Air Force]] from 1951 to 1953.<ref name=\"DEBRETTS\">Cf. ''Debrett's People of Today'' entry for Prof. Critchlow</ref> In the Air Force he met [[Frank Bowling]] and subsequently helped inspire Bowling to develop his career as a painter.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bernard|first=Imelda|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/my-life-has-always-been-about-painting-frank-bowling/|title=\u2018My life has always been about painting\u2019 - An interview with Frank Bowling.|date=1 Jul 2017|work=Apollo. The International Art Magazine|access-date=13 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHaving been originally trained as a classical painter,<ref>Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', Lindisfarne Press, 1994, {{ISBN|0-940262-63-0}}. Cf. author profiles.</ref> he went on to study sacred geometry and authored many books on geometry, including ''Order in Space'', ''Islamic Pattern as a Cosmological Art'', ''Time Stands Still'' and ''the Hidden Geometry of Flowers.'' He also contributed the forewords to English editions of works by [[Titus Burckhardt]], [[Frithjof Schuon]], and others.<ref>foreword in ''The Foundations of Christian Art: Illustrated'' by Titus Burckhardt, edited by Michael Fitzgerald; foreword in ''Art from the Sacred to the Profane: East and West'' by Frithjof Schuon, edited by Catherine Schuon; foreword in ''Chartres: and the birth of the cathedral'' by Titus Burckhardt; translated from the German by William Stoddart. Ipswich: Golgonooza, 1995.</ref>\n\nCritchlow was a lecturer at the [[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association (AA) School of Architecture]] in London for twelve years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaschool.ac.uk/PUBLIC/NEWSNOTICES/obituaries.php?page=3|title=Michael Thomas Cartledge AADipl (1925\u20132016)|last=|first=|date=|website=Architectural Association School of Architecture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Whilst at the AA, he was invited to teach at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] in Ghana by [[Buckminster Fuller|R. Buckminster Fuller]], the American engineer, architect and futurist. \n\n[[Buckminster Fuller]] wrote of Keith:<blockquote>\"Keith Critchlow has one of the century\u2019s rare conceptual minds. He is continually inspired by the conceptioning of both earliest and latest record. He lauds the work of others while himself pouring forth, in great modesty, whole vista-filling new realizations of nature\u2019s mathematical structuring.\u2026 He is one of the most inspiring scholar-teachers I have had the privilege to know\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thamesandhudson.com/order-in-space-a-design-source-book-9780500340332|title=Order in Space|last=|first=|date=|website=Thames & Hudson|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 Apr 2020}}</ref></blockquote>Whilst in Ghana, Critchlow and his colleague Dr Michael Ben-Eli studied Fuller geometry and experimented in the construction of [[Geodesic dome|geodesic domes]] using local building materials, such as palm, bamboo and aluminium. One of their aims was to help reduce use of concrete and minimise the negative impact of construction on the environment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Volckmann|first=Russ|date=2010|title=Design and Sustainability: An Interview with Michael Ben-Eli|url=https://integral-review.org/issues/vol_6_no_1_volckmann_ben-eli_interview.pdf|journal=INTEGRAL REVIEW Toward Development of Politics and the Political|volume=6 (1)|pages=291-303|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Critchlow formed Polyhedral Developments (a private company) in partnership with architectural designer Hayward Hill; together they pioneered the use of polyhedral domes as emergency shelters for families who had lost their homes to disaster.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/latenightlive/making-space-for-the-sacred/3559808|title=Making Space For The Sacred. On Late Night Live with Phillip Adams|date=29 Sep 1999|work=ABC Radio National, Australia|access-date=11 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Critchlow and colleagues experimented in the use of lightweight materials for the construction of domes, including Tri-Wall Pak corrugated board, to aid in transport and assembly by unskilled labour in disaster areas.<ref>FOLDED SURFACE STRUCTURES - The Potential Use of Paperboard for Low Cost Enclosures. By Vinzenz Franz-Josef Sedlak, Dipl. 3hg. (Arch.). A thesis submitted for the Degree of Master of Philosophy in Structural Engineering in the Department of Civil Engineering; University of Surrey, March 1975.</ref>\n\nCritchlow was professor of Islamic Art at the [[Royal College of Art]] in London from 1975 for many years.<ref name=\"MALE1990\">Male, Lydia Sharman, [http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199003/in.the.mind.of.the.beholder.htm \"In the Mind of the Beholder\"], ''[[Saudi Aramco World]]'', May/June 1990</ref> He also delivered lectures on the application of sacred geometry in architecture at the [[Lindisfarne Association]] in New York City and then Crestone, Colorado, in the United States from 1978<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bamford|first=Christopher|title=Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science|publisher=Steiner Books|year=1994|isbn=9780940262638|location=|pages=front cover vi\u2013ix}}</ref>. In Crestone, he contributed to a number of summer schools for Lindisfarne and taught alongside innovative thinkers from both the arts and sciences, including social philosopher and cultural critic, [[William Irwin Thompson]] (founder of the Lindisfarne Association), mythographer and symbolist [[Robert Lawlor]], poet and environmental activist [[Wendell Berry]], biologist [[John Todd (Canadian biologist)|John Todd]], and environmentalist [[James Lovelock]].\n\nCritchlow founded the Visual Islamic and Traditional Arts (VITA) department in 1984,<ref name=\"MALE1990\" /> which moved from the Royal College of Art to The Prince's Institute of Architecture in 1992\u20133, where he was director of research. The institute later evolved into [[The Prince's Foundation]], within which [[The Prince's School of Traditional Arts|Prince's School of Traditional Arts]] (PSTA) is housed. He was professor emeritus at PSTA and served as director of research.<ref>[http://www.psta.org.uk/about/trusteesandstaff/ Prince's School of Traditional Arts \u2013 Trustees and Staff] \"Dr Keith Critchlow, Professor Emeritus, Founder, and Director of Research\"</ref> He also taught at [[The Prince's Foundation for the Built Environment]].\n\nIn 1983, Critchlow was asked by Indian philosopher and author [[Jiddu Krishnamurti]] to design the [[Jiddu Krishnamurti|Krishnamurti]] Study Centre in Hampshire, UK, which was completed in 1986.<ref>[http://www.krishnamurticentre.org.uk/ The Krishnamurti Centre in England]</ref> His other architectural works include, the Lindisfarne Chapel in [[Crestone, Colorado|Crestone]], Colorado, in the United States with a special design for the vaulting of the dome,<ref>[http://www.dharmasangha.org/location.html#Dome Creston Mountain Zen Center] \u2013 location and history of the dome Lindisfarne Chapel</ref> and a hospital, the [[Sathya Sai Baba|Sri Sathya Sai]] Institute of Higher Medical Sciences in [[Puttaparthi|Puttaparthi, India]]. [[Isaac Tigrett]], who had founded the [[Hard Rock Cafe]] enterprise, secured Critchlow's expertise to design the hospital in Puttuparthi.<ref>Lerwill, John, [http://www.lerwill-life.org.uk/spirit/sai.htm \"Who is Sai\"]</ref> His use of sacred geometry played a major role in these architectural designs and projects.\n\nCritchlow made an important contribution to the re-construction of the Minbar of Saladin in the al-Aqsa Mosque, Jerusalem. The minbar was destroyed by fire in 1969 following an arson attack by an evangelical Christian. King Hussein of Jordan launched a 30-year search, including international competitions, to find a sufficiently qualified person to re-design the intricate patterns of the minbar. The competition was finally won by Dr Minwer Al-Meheid<ref>{{Cite book|last=Meehan|first=Mark W.|title=Islam, Modernity, and the Liminal Space Between|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|year=2013|isbn=|location=Newcastle Upon Tyne|pages=96-97}}</ref> who was inspired to make his submission after spending a year the studying Critchlow's work:<blockquote>\"Seemingly, the ancient knowledge of how to map the structure geometrically had been lost. Until, that is, Minwer al-Meheid, an engineer from Jordan, walked into a bookshop in Damascus and fell upon a work that contained the answers. It was ''Islamic Patterns'', a pioneering and seminal study of the geometry underpinning Islamic art, by Keith Critchlow.\" '''Resurgence & Ecologist Magazine, 2015'''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skelly|first=Ian|date=2015|title=A Treasure Cave of Sacred Geometry|url=https://www.resurgence.org/magazine/article4334-a-treasure-cave-of-sacred-geometry.html|journal=Resurgence & Ecologist|volume=288|pages=|via=}}</ref></blockquote>The story of the re-construction of the Minbar of Saladin is told in a documentary film ''Stairway to Heave''n, from which the following quotes re taken:<ref>''Stairway to Heaven''. October 5, 2007. '''Partners:''' West Park Pictures and Prince\u2019s Charities Events distributed through NBD TV. '''Wrapped:''' September 2007. '''Length:''' 53 minutes.</ref><blockquote>\"If it wasn't that I found his [''Critchlow's''] book a year before that and I had a year of practicing how these things would be done and realising how these things could be done, there is no way I would have entered the competition and no way I would have known how to do it ... thanks to Keith I did it ... I  got fascinated by the book [''Islamic Patterns''] and fascinated by the man who wrote it. So I wanted to meet Keith since that time because I thought this man knows a lot more than what is in that book. Keith is fascinating, he's dynamic. He doesn't stress his point of view, he just points certain things and certain facts, truths of geometry.\" '''Dr Minwer Al-Meheid'''<ref>Extract from the film ''Stairway to Heaven'' (2007) available on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CJMPvhV7jZg and https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GPL5rUE8PQM</ref></blockquote>Critchlow inspired many architectural students during his time as a lecturer, including David Marks and Julia Barfield (Marks Barfield Architects), who designed the London Eye and the British Airways i360 in Brighton. One of his last major projects was with Marks Barfield Architects supporting the design of the [[Cambridge Central Mosque]], Europe's first eco-friendly mosque<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambridgecentralmosque.org/|title=Cambridge Central Mosque|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 Apr 2020}}</ref>. The underlying geometry of the mosque, \u2019the breath of the compassionate\u2019, rooted in Islamic tradition, was designed by Critchlow. He also advised on the patterns underlying the roof structure and contributed decorative elements, including windows and the [[mihrab]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moore|first=Rowan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/mar/17/cambridge-new-mosque-marks-barfield|title=Inside Cambridge\u2019s new \u00a323m mosque: a forest runs through it.|date=7 Mar 2019|work=The Guardian Newspaper|access-date=11 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shahed|first=Saleem|date=4 June 2019|title=Ecological, ethical Cambridge Mosque ties west and east.|url=https://www.ribaj.com/culture/marks-barfield-cambridge-central-mosque-shahed-saleem|journal=The RIBA Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nCritchlow was president of the [[Temenos Academy]]<ref>[http://www.temenosacademy.org/temenos_key_individuals.html Temenos Academy] \u2013 key individuals: Patron: His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales, President: Professor Keith Critchlow, Chairman: Sir Nicholas Pearson, Bt.</ref>, a co-founder of Research into Lost Knowledge ([http://www.rilko.org/ RILKO]) and founder of Kairos, an educational charity which investigates, studies, and promotes traditional values in art and science. He served there as director of studies.\n\n== Family ==\nCritchlow was married to Gail Susan Critchlow from whom he gained much love and support over their 62-year marriage. He leaves behind four children.\n\n== Selected works ==\n[[File:Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital panorama.jpg|thumb|1126px|left|Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital, Puttaparthi, A.P., India. Designed by Critchlow]]<br />{{clear}}\n\n===Books===\n\n* ''Order in Space A Design Source Book'', Thames & Hudson, 1969\n* ''Into the Hidden Environment: The Oceans'', illustrations by David Nockels, 1973 ([[Viking Press|Viking Studio]])\n*Chartres Labyrinth, A Model of the Universe and the Journey of the Soul, 1975, reprinted 2002\n*''Islamic Patterns'', Thames & Hudson, 1976\n* ''Earth Mysteries : A Study in Patterns'', 1978\n* ''Time Stands Still: New Light on Megalithic Science'', 1979\n* ''Soul As Sphere and Androgyne'', 1980\n* ''Research : Principles, Policy and Practice'', London : Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, 1993\n* ''The Whole Question of Health: Enquiry into Architectural First Principles in the Designing of Health Care Buildings'', Keith Critchlow and Jon Allen, London: The Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture\n* ''Islamic Art and Architecture: System of Geometric Design'', Issam El-Said (Author), Tarek El-Bouri (Editor), Keith Critchlow (Editor), Garnet Publishing Ltd, 1999\n* ''The Hidden Geometry of Flowers: Living Rhythms Form and Number'', Floris Books, 2011\n*''The Golden Meaning : An Introduction'', London: Kairos Publications, 2014\n*''The Knap of Howar and The Origins of Geometry'', A collaboration between Nicholas Cope ([http://www.ncope.co.uk www.ncope.co.uk]) and Keith Critchlow, London: Kairos Publications, 2016 \n\n===Chapters===\n\n* \"The Platonic Tradition on the Nature of Proportion\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n* \"What is Sacred Architecture?\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n* \"Twelve Criteria for Sacred Architecture\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n\n===Film===\n\n* Reflection. A film by Keith Critchlow and Lawrence Moore. Music by [[Mike Oldfield]] & [[Alan Hacker]]. A Vortex Production. [[Arts Council of Great Britain]] 1977. (References taken from the credits appearing at the end of the film).\n\n=== Contributions ===\n* Allen,Jon; (Foreword by Keith Critchlow). [http://www.florisbooks.co.uk/author/Jon-Allen/ ''Drawing Geometry: A Primer of Basic Forms for Artists, Designers and Architects''], Floris Books (30 October 2007). {{ISBN|978-0863156083}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Islamic geometric patterns]]\n* [[Temenos Academy Review]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/c/9267/Keith+Barry.aspx \"Biographical Entry: Prof Keith Critchlow\"], [[Debrett's|''Debrett's People of Today'']], Debrett's Limited, 18\u201320 Hill Rise, Richmond, Surrey TW10 6UA United Kingdom\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Male, Lydia Sharman, [http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199003/in.the.mind.of.the.beholder.htm \"In the Mind of the Beholder\"], ''[[Saudi Aramco World]]'', March 1990. An article about VITA, Critchlow, and his students.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127041035/http://www.kairos-foundation.com/ |date=27 January 2010 |title=KAIROS Foundation }} \u2013 Workshop courses taught by Dr. Critchlow\n*[http://www.worldwisdom.com/public/authors/details.aspx?ID=144 \"Profile of Dr. Keith Critchlow\"] \u2013 World Wisdom Press\n*[https://steiner.presswarehouse.com/books/AuthorDetail.aspx?id=24303 Profile: Keith Critchlow] \u2013 Steiner Books, Anthroposophic Press\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Critchlow, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Royal Air Force personnel]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:British architects]]\n[[Category:Mythographers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Summerhill School]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Symbologists]]\n[[Category:Sacred geometry]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Keith Critchlow\n| image              = <!-- Keith Critchlow-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Keith Barry Critchlow\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1933|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2020|4|8|1933|3|16}}\n| death_place        = Kingston-Upon-Thames, London\n| nationality        = UK\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = sacred architecture design and analysis, founder of Visual Islamic and Traditional Arts (VITA) school, co-founder of the [[Temenos Academy]]\n| occupation         = professor of architecture, author\n| alma_mater         = [[Summerhill School]]<br>[[St Martins School of Art]]<br>[[Royal College of Art]]\n}}\n\n'''Keith Barry Critchlow''' (16 March 1933 \u2013 8 April 2020) was an artist, lecturer, author, professor of architecture and a co-founder of the [[Temenos Academy]] in the UK. He was also a leading expert in [[sacred architecture]] and [[sacred geometry]]. \n\n==Biography==\nCritchlow was educated at the [[Summerhill School]], [[Saint Martin's School of Art|St Martins School of Art]], and the [[Royal College of Art]].<ref>[http://www.cosm.org/about/boardofadvisors.html \"Biography: Keith Critchlow\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525134534/http://www.cosm.org/about/boardofadvisors.html |date=25 May 2011 }}, Board of Advisers, [[Alex Grey|Chapel of Sacred Mirrors]], New York.</ref> \n\nWhilst at St Martins he studied alongside renowned artists [[Leon Kossoff]], [[Frank Auerbach]] and [[Joe Tilson]], with whom he developed great friendships and gained much artistic inspiration as a painter. At St Martins, he also met [[Z'ev ben Shimon Halevi]] (born Warren Kenton), who subsequently authored books on the Toledano Tradition of Kabbalah and became a founder member of the Kabbalah Society; they were lifelong friends.\n\nCritchlow performed [[national service]] in the [[Royal Air Force]] from 1951 to 1953.<ref name=\"DEBRETTS\">Cf. ''Debrett's People of Today'' entry for Prof. Critchlow</ref> In the Air Force he met [[Frank Bowling]] and subsequently helped inspire Bowling to develop his career as a painter.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bernard|first=Imelda|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/my-life-has-always-been-about-painting-frank-bowling/|title=\u2018My life has always been about painting\u2019 - An interview with Frank Bowling.|date=1 Jul 2017|work=Apollo. The International Art Magazine|access-date=13 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHaving been originally trained as a classical painter,<ref>Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', Lindisfarne Press, 1994, {{ISBN|0-940262-63-0}}. Cf. author profiles.</ref> he went on to study sacred geometry and authored many books on geometry, including ''Order in Space'', ''Islamic Pattern as a Cosmological Art'', ''Time Stands Still'' and ''the Hidden Geometry of Flowers.'' He also contributed the forewords to English editions of works by [[Titus Burckhardt]], [[Frithjof Schuon]], and others.<ref>foreword in ''The Foundations of Christian Art: Illustrated'' by Titus Burckhardt, edited by Michael Fitzgerald; foreword in ''Art from the Sacred to the Profane: East and West'' by Frithjof Schuon, edited by Catherine Schuon; foreword in ''Chartres: and the birth of the cathedral'' by Titus Burckhardt; translated from the German by William Stoddart. Ipswich: Golgonooza, 1995.</ref>\n\nCritchlow was a lecturer at the [[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association (AA) School of Architecture]] in London for twelve years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaschool.ac.uk/PUBLIC/NEWSNOTICES/obituaries.php?page=3|title=Michael Thomas Cartledge AADipl (1925\u20132016)|last=|first=|date=|website=Architectural Association School of Architecture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Whilst at the AA, he was invited to teach at [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] in Ghana by [[Buckminster Fuller|R. Buckminster Fuller]], the American engineer, architect and futurist. \n\n[[Buckminster Fuller]] wrote of Keith:<blockquote>\"Keith Critchlow has one of the century\u2019s rare conceptual minds. He is continually inspired by the conceptioning of both earliest and latest record. He lauds the work of others while himself pouring forth, in great modesty, whole vista-filling new realizations of nature\u2019s mathematical structuring.\u2026 He is one of the most inspiring scholar-teachers I have had the privilege to know\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thamesandhudson.com/order-in-space-a-design-source-book-9780500340332|title=Order in Space|last=|first=|date=|website=Thames & Hudson|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 Apr 2020}}</ref></blockquote>Whilst in Ghana, Critchlow and his colleague Dr Michael Ben-Eli studied Fuller geometry and experimented in the construction of [[Geodesic dome|geodesic domes]] using local building materials, such as palm, bamboo and aluminium. One of their aims was to help reduce use of concrete and minimise the negative impact of construction on the environment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Volckmann|first=Russ|date=2010|title=Design and Sustainability: An Interview with Michael Ben-Eli|url=https://integral-review.org/issues/vol_6_no_1_volckmann_ben-eli_interview.pdf|journal=INTEGRAL REVIEW Toward Development of Politics and the Political|volume=6 (1)|pages=291-303|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Critchlow formed Polyhedral Developments (a private company) in partnership with architectural designer Hayward Hill; together they pioneered the use of polyhedral domes as emergency shelters for families who had lost their homes to disaster.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/latenightlive/making-space-for-the-sacred/3559808|title=Making Space For The Sacred. On Late Night Live with Phillip Adams|date=29 Sep 1999|work=ABC Radio National, Australia|access-date=11 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Critchlow and colleagues experimented in the use of lightweight materials for the construction of domes, including Tri-Wall Pak corrugated board, to aid in transport and assembly by unskilled labour in disaster areas.<ref>FOLDED SURFACE STRUCTURES - The Potential Use of Paperboard for Low Cost Enclosures. By Vinzenz Franz-Josef Sedlak, Dipl. 3hg. (Arch.). A thesis submitted for the Degree of Master of Philosophy in Structural Engineering in the Department of Civil Engineering; University of Surrey, March 1975.</ref>\n\nCritchlow was professor of Islamic Art at the [[Royal College of Art]] in London from 1975 for many years.<ref name=\"MALE1990\">Male, Lydia Sharman, [http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199003/in.the.mind.of.the.beholder.htm \"In the Mind of the Beholder\"], ''[[Saudi Aramco World]]'', May/June 1990</ref> He also delivered lectures on the application of sacred geometry in architecture at the [[Lindisfarne Association]] in New York City and then Crestone, Colorado, in the United States from 1978<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bamford|first=Christopher|title=Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science|publisher=Steiner Books|year=1994|isbn=9780940262638|location=|pages=front cover vi\u2013ix}}</ref>. In Crestone, he contributed to a number of summer schools for Lindisfarne and taught alongside innovative thinkers from both the arts and sciences, including social philosopher and cultural critic, [[William Irwin Thompson]] (founder of the Lindisfarne Association), mythographer and symbolist [[Robert Lawlor]], poet and environmental activist [[Wendell Berry]], biologist [[John Todd (Canadian biologist)|John Todd]], and environmentalist [[James Lovelock]].\n\nCritchlow founded the Visual Islamic and Traditional Arts (VITA) department in 1984,<ref name=\"MALE1990\" /> which moved from the Royal College of Art to The Prince's Institute of Architecture in 1992\u20133, where he was director of research. The institute later evolved into [[The Prince's Foundation]], within which [[The Prince's School of Traditional Arts|Prince's School of Traditional Arts]] (PSTA) is housed. He was professor emeritus at PSTA and served as director of research.<ref>[http://www.psta.org.uk/about/trusteesandstaff/ Prince's School of Traditional Arts \u2013 Trustees and Staff] \"Dr Keith Critchlow, Professor Emeritus, Founder, and Director of Research\"</ref> He also taught at [[The Prince's Foundation for the Built Environment]].\n\nIn 1983, Critchlow was asked by Indian philosopher and author [[Jiddu Krishnamurti]] to design the [[Jiddu Krishnamurti|Krishnamurti]] Study Centre in Hampshire, UK, which was completed in 1986.<ref>[http://www.krishnamurticentre.org.uk/ The Krishnamurti Centre in England]</ref> His other architectural works include, the Lindisfarne Chapel in [[Crestone, Colorado|Crestone]], Colorado, in the United States with a special design for the vaulting of the dome,<ref>[http://www.dharmasangha.org/location.html#Dome Creston Mountain Zen Center] \u2013 location and history of the dome Lindisfarne Chapel</ref> and a hospital, the [[Sathya Sai Baba|Sri Sathya Sai]] Institute of Higher Medical Sciences in [[Puttaparthi|Puttaparthi, India]]. [[Isaac Tigrett]], who had founded the [[Hard Rock Cafe]] enterprise, secured Critchlow's expertise to design the hospital in Puttuparthi.<ref>Lerwill, John, [http://www.lerwill-life.org.uk/spirit/sai.htm \"Who is Sai\"]</ref> His use of sacred geometry played a major role in these architectural designs and projects.\n\nCritchlow made an important contribution to the re-construction of the Minbar of Saladin in the al-Aqsa Mosque, Jerusalem. The minbar was destroyed by fire in 1969 following an arson attack by an evangelical Christian. King Hussein of Jordan launched a 30-year search, including international competitions, to find a sufficiently qualified person to re-design the intricate patterns of the minbar. The competition was finally won by Dr Minwer Al-Meheid<ref>{{Cite book|last=Meehan|first=Mark W.|title=Islam, Modernity, and the Liminal Space Between|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|year=2013|isbn=|location=Newcastle Upon Tyne|pages=96-97}}</ref> who was inspired by the work of Critchlow:<blockquote>\"Seemingly, the ancient knowledge of how to map the structure geometrically had been lost. Until, that is, Minwer al-Meheid, an engineer from Jordan, walked into a bookshop in Damascus and fell upon a work that contained the answers. It was ''Islamic Patterns'', a pioneering and seminal study of the geometry underpinning Islamic art, by Keith Critchlow.\" '''Resurgence & Ecologist Magazine, 2015'''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skelly|first=Ian|date=2015|title=A Treasure Cave of Sacred Geometry|url=https://www.resurgence.org/magazine/article4334-a-treasure-cave-of-sacred-geometry.html|journal=Resurgence & Ecologist|volume=288|pages=|via=}}</ref></blockquote>The story of the re-construction of the Minbar of Saladin is told in a documentary film ''Stairway to Heave''n, from which the following quote is taken:<ref>''Stairway to Heaven''. October 5, 2007. '''Partners:''' West Park Pictures and Prince\u2019s Charities Events distributed through NBD TV. '''Wrapped:''' September 2007. '''Length:''' 53 minutes.</ref><blockquote>\"I got fascinated by the book [''Islamic Patterns''] and fascinated by the man who wrote it. So I wanted to meet Keith since that time because I thought this man knows a lot more than what is in that book. Keith is fascinating, his dynamic. He doesn't stress his point of view, he just points certain things and certain facts, truths of geometry.\" '''Dr Minwer Al-Meheid'''<ref>Extract from the film ''Stairway to Heaven'' (2007) available on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GPL5rUE8PQM</ref></blockquote>Critchlow inspired many architectural students during his time as a lecturer, including David Marks and Julia Barfield (Marks Barfield Architects), who designed the London Eye and the British Airways i360 in Brighton. He worked with Marks Barfield Architects on the design of the [[Cambridge Central Mosque]], Europe's first eco-friendly mosque<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambridgecentralmosque.org/|title=Cambridge Central Mosque|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 Apr 2020}}</ref>. The underlying geometry of the mosque, \u2019the breath of the compassionate\u2019, which is rooted in Islamic tradition, was designed by Critchlow. He also advised on the patterns underlying the roof structure and contributed decorative elements, including windows and the [[mihrab]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moore|first=Rowan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/mar/17/cambridge-new-mosque-marks-barfield|title=Inside Cambridge\u2019s new \u00a323m mosque: a forest runs through it.|date=7 Mar 2019|work=The Guardian Newspaper|access-date=11 Apr 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shahed|first=Saleem|date=4 June 2019|title=Ecological, ethical Cambridge Mosque ties west and east.|url=https://www.ribaj.com/culture/marks-barfield-cambridge-central-mosque-shahed-saleem|journal=The RIBA Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nCritchlow was president of the [[Temenos Academy]]<ref>[http://www.temenosacademy.org/temenos_key_individuals.html Temenos Academy] \u2013 key individuals: Patron: His Royal Highness The Prince of Wales, President: Professor Keith Critchlow, Chairman: Sir Nicholas Pearson, Bt.</ref>, a co-founder of Research into Lost Knowledge ([http://www.rilko.org/ RILKO]) and founder of Kairos, an educational charity which investigates, studies, and promotes traditional values in art and science. He served there as director of studies.\n\n== Family ==\nCritchlow was married to Gail Susan Critchlow from whom he gained much love and support over their 62-year marriage. He leaves behind four children.\n\n== Selected works ==\n[[File:Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital panorama.jpg|thumb|1126px|left|Sri Sathya Sai Super Speciality Hospital, Puttaparthi, A.P., India. Designed by Critchlow]]<br />{{clear}}\n\n===Books===\n\n* ''Order in Space A Design Source Book'', Thames & Hudson, 1969\n* ''Into the Hidden Environment: The Oceans'', illustrations by David Nockels, 1973 ([[Viking Press|Viking Studio]])\n*Chartres Labyrinth, A Model of the Universe and the Journey of the Soul, 1975, reprinted 2002\n*''Islamic Patterns'', Thames & Hudson, 1976\n* ''Earth Mysteries : A Study in Patterns'', 1978\n* ''Time Stands Still: New Light on Megalithic Science'', 1979\n* ''Soul As Sphere and Androgyne'', 1980\n* ''Research : Principles, Policy and Practice'', London : Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture, 1993\n* ''The Whole Question of Health: Enquiry into Architectural First Principles in the Designing of Health Care Buildings'', Keith Critchlow and Jon Allen, London: The Prince of Wales's Institute of Architecture\n* ''Islamic Art and Architecture: System of Geometric Design'', Issam El-Said (Author), Tarek El-Bouri (Editor), Keith Critchlow (Editor), Garnet Publishing Ltd, 1999\n* ''The Hidden Geometry of Flowers: Living Rhythms Form and Number'', Floris Books, 2011\n*''The Golden Meaning : An Introduction'', London: Kairos Publications, 2014\n*''The Knap of Howar and The Origins of Geometry'', A collaboration between Nicholas Cope ([http://www.ncope.co.uk www.ncope.co.uk]) and Keith Critchlow, London: Kairos Publications, 2016 \n\n===Chapters===\n\n* \"The Platonic Tradition on the Nature of Proportion\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n* \"What is Sacred Architecture?\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n* \"Twelve Criteria for Sacred Architecture\", in Bamford, Christopher, ''Homage to Pythagoras: Rediscovering Sacred Science'', 1994.\n\n===Film===\n\n* Reflection. A film by Keith Critchlow and Lawrence Moore. Music by [[Mike Oldfield]] & [[Alan Hacker]]. A Vortex Production. [[Arts Council of Great Britain]] 1977. (References taken from the credits appearing at the end of the film).\n\n=== Contributions ===\n* Allen,Jon; (Foreword by Keith Critchlow). [http://www.florisbooks.co.uk/author/Jon-Allen/ ''Drawing Geometry: A Primer of Basic Forms for Artists, Designers and Architects''], Floris Books (30 October 2007). {{ISBN|978-0863156083}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Islamic geometric patterns]]\n* [[Temenos Academy Review]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/c/9267/Keith+Barry.aspx \"Biographical Entry: Prof Keith Critchlow\"], [[Debrett's|''Debrett's People of Today'']], Debrett's Limited, 18\u201320 Hill Rise, Richmond, Surrey TW10 6UA United Kingdom\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Male, Lydia Sharman, [http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199003/in.the.mind.of.the.beholder.htm \"In the Mind of the Beholder\"], ''[[Saudi Aramco World]]'', March 1990. An article about VITA, Critchlow, and his students.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127041035/http://www.kairos-foundation.com/ |date=27 January 2010 |title=KAIROS Foundation }} \u2013 Workshop courses taught by Dr. Critchlow\n*[http://www.worldwisdom.com/public/authors/details.aspx?ID=144 \"Profi